OOC
Usage: ooc <message>

  OOC is the Out Of Character channel. All comments here are to remain as
such. Channels can be turned off and turned on again by typing TOGGLE OOC 
respectively.

#0
PIKER

Term used to describe those who are logging off the MUD.
Usually, there is no excuse for 'piking' - if they are
leaving for any reason, it is piking. Leaving for the most
trivial of reasons, such as work, food, or sleep, are the
most ridiculous cases - cases in which you should yell
"Piker!!" on every channel you can.

In extreme cases, one may use 'piker' to describe someone
that has not been on the MUD in a considerable amount of
time. These are the most obvious cases, but there are many
other types of piker that can only be learned over time.
#0
afw
  The AFW flag (Away From Window) is handy to use to show others
that you are not reachable. You can customise your AFW flag by typing :
  &rTOGGLE AFW <message>&n
For example, if my name is Kazhi and I wish to be AFW, I can give a
reason for being AFW. I would just type:
   &rTOGGLE AFW Kazhi is AFW Doing homework.&n
If you then telled Kazhi while he was AFK, the following messaage
would be displayed:
     Kazhi is AFW Doing homework.
     &rYou tell Kazhi,"Hiya!"&n
AFW can be turned off by typing TOGGLE AFW again.
#0
chess
There is a game of chess in the game, which two players can use for their
amusement. The valid syntax and expected order of things is:
chess ask <opponent>    This makes you ask opponent if he wants to play chess.
chess accept <opponent>   This makes you accept a request to play. Now the game is on.
chess show      This shows the current board to you.
chess move <pos1> <pos2>    This makes you move a piece on pos1 to pos2.
...
...
chess resign        Makes you quit the game.

There are a few other things you can do, such as "chess move shortcastle" for
a short castling move, and "chess move longcastle" to make a long castling move.
The basics are in, such as not allowing movement that leaves your king in
a threatened position, and basic chess piece moves.
The one who asks is always white player, and the one who accepts is always black player.

You can also "chess pass" if you want to skip your turn.
If you want to watch someone elses game, type "chess watch <player>" to see the board.
