Usage: buy <item name>
       buy #<item number>
       buy n.<item name>
       buy n <item name>
       buy n #<item number>

If you'd like to purchase an item from a shop and have the money, you can buy
it.  Items can be bought by name, or by their number in the shop listing,
and can be bought in quantity.
 
Examples:
 
  > buy sword        (buy the first sword on the list)
  > buy #3           (buy the third item on the list)
  > buy 4.sword      (buy the fourth sword on the list)
  > buy 10 bread     (buy 10 pieces of bread)
  > buy 10 #2        (buy 10 of the second item on the list)
 
See also: LIST, SELL, SHOPS, VALUE
#0
CARDGAME

Usage: cardgame [command]

This is the entrypoint for all commands related to the game of cards.
The possible syntaxes are:

\c01cardgame start [maxnumber]\c00
   Starts a new game of cards, unless you already are in one.
   The maxnumber indicates the highest allowed number of players
   in the game; once it has been reached, no new players can join.
\c01cardgame end\c00
   If you started the game, this ends it.
\c01cardgame join [name]\c00
   Makes you join a new game of cards that [name] currently is playing,
   if the max numbers of players hasn't been reached.
\c01cardgame leave\c00
   Makes you leave the game of cards you're currently in.
   Note that if you started the game, you can't leave this way, 
   you must use 'cardgame end'.
\c01cardgame get [number]\c00
  Gets the number of cards from the deck you indicate.
  If there are not enough unused cards left in the deck, 
  you take the ones that remain.
\c01cardgame replace [number]\c00
  Replaces the indexed card that you hold in your hand with a fresh
  card from the deck, if there are any left.
\c01cardgame drop [number]\c00
  Drops the indexed card that you hold in your hand.
\c01cardgame list\c00
  Shows you (and only you) the cards you currently hold in your hand.
\c01cardgame show [number]\c00
  If no number is typed, you show and drop the entire hand, 
  otherwise you "play" the indexed card, thereby dropping it.
\c01cardgame shuffle\c00
  Shuffles all the cards that have been picked up and dropped or played,
  making them eligible for picking up again.

See also: DICE
