#0
CONSIDER

Usage: consider <monster>

This command will compare your Level with the <monsters> level.  You will then
receive a rough estimate, which is by no means exact.  Consider does not take
hitpoints/special attacks/damage into account.

Example:

  > consider fido

The results you can get are the following:
30 to 15 levels lower: Now where did that chicken go?
15 to 10 levels lower: You could do it with a needle!
10 to  5 levels lower: Easy.
5  to  1 levels lower: Fairly easy.
          Equal level: The perfect match!
1  to  5 levels higher: You would need some luck!
5  to 10 levels higher: You would need a lot of luck!
10 to 15 levels higher: You would need a lot of luck and great equipment!
15 to 20 levels higher: Do you feel lucky, punk?
20 to 30 levels higher: Are you mad!?
30 or more levels higher: You ARE mad!

See also: HIT, KILL
#0
CRAFT

This command is only available to those who have the Craft skill.

By typing this, you enter a menu in which you can create items of
your own choosing. You select what to change by typing the number
before the ).

Here's a brief explanation of each possible choice:
\c011\c00) Keywords. Keywords are what the game looks for when you type get
drop, wield,etc...Set this to something that is typical for this item.
The keywords are to be separated by a whitespace, so multiword keywords
don't work
For example: A two-handed sword should have keywords "blade sword two-hand"

\c012\c00) Short description. That is what is shown when you manipulate
the item. For instance "Otto wields a two-handed sword." Here "a
two-handed sword" is the short description.

\c013\c00) Description is what you see when item is listed in the room contents.
Example: A two-handed sword, slightly rusty form disuse, lies here.

\c014\c00) Type. Select what kind of item you want to create. A list of
all possible choices will appear for you to choose from.

\c015\c00) Wear flags. This lets you choose where the item is supposedly
worn. You can choose several different locations, and a list of all
possible choices is shown. \c01Note:\c00 Always keep the \c02TAKE\c00 flag,
or noone will ever be able to pick it up if you drop it.

\c016\c00) Affection when worn: Here you can determine what nice affections
the item should give to you when it's worn. The more affections you choose,
the higher the total cost to craft this item. You can have 6 affections 
maximum, and each must be unique.
The \c02costs\c00 for these affections are: 
500 per step for a base stat such as Strength, Charisma, Constitution and so forth, 
400 per step for hitroll and damroll,
50 per step for AC and Abs, 
10 per step for mana, move and hitpoints.
You can never have the item to cost more than \c025000\c00 coins total.

\c017\c00) The title of this one depends on the type of object you've
chosen.
Don't forget to set the stats here either, or your item may well be useless.
Here you set such things as how long a light source has to burn, damage
of weapons, abs and ac of armor and so forth.
Note that the item costs more the higher stats you have here.
For instance, weapon damage cost is 100*number of damage dice*size of
damage dice, and so forth.
\c018\c00) Exit and create object. If you're satisfied with the object,
type this to pay the cost, get the item and return to the normal game.
\c019\c00) Exit without creating object. If you changed your mind and
don't want to create the object, type this number.

See also: TOOL
