roleplay 

Introduction
________________________________________________________________________

  There are many aspects to Roleplay that can be only gained
through experience. This document has been written in hopes of
limiting some of the original mistakes made by someone new to
Roleplay, helping you to fit in with the game's players and
atmosphere quickly.

Please read the following files.

Starting Out
     rp_what        = What to keep in mind when starting out a
                      Character.
     rp_background  = Creating a solid Background for your Character.
     rp_description = Creating a good description for your Character.

Beginning Roleplay
     rp_basic       = What is IC/OOC? What is Roleplay?
     rp_emotebasic  = What is an Emote?
     rp_emoteincl   = What an emote should include.
     rp_whatfirst   = What do you do when you first enter an area?

Tips and Advice
     rp_etiquette   = Roleplay Etiquette and Advice.
     rp_where       = Where to find Roleplay.
     rp_setup       = How to setup Roleplay.

Advanced Topics
     rp_tooledeq    = Tooled equipment and you.
     rp_npcs        = Non-player Characters.
     rp_relatives   = Relatives and your Character.
     rp_rooms       = Rooms and Houses for your Character.
     rp_jobs        = IC Jobs for your Character.
________________________________________________________________________

To read the above files, type 'help rp_<theoneyouwant>'
   Example: Type help rp_what to find out about the first topic in
            Starting Out.
#0
rp_tooledeq

Advanced Topics:

   There are many aspects of Roleplay to become a part of, and once
you feel comfortable with simply expressing yourself through words,
you can create a more in-depth environment around yourself. There are
several ways to do this, we've only touched on a few here.

A. Tooled Equipment

   To create a more complete character, many players decide to get the
equipment that they wear tooled into something more appropriate and IC
for their character. They go about this in an IC way, finding a
craftsman skilled in whatever they need to have altered. Once finding
a craftsman, the player usually RP's that they've torn a hem, or that
they want something new to wear. The craftsman is almost always more
than willing to roleplay this out, this is the concept for their
character after all. In the Roleplay, you can send tells to the
craftsman on how you want your tooled equipment to look like, it
usually coincides very closely with your description. For instance, if
you've put that you're wearing a silken blue gown in your description,
you might want to have the equipment you are wearing on your body
tooled into a luxurious, silken blue gown that hugs the curves. Or
something like that. You can add color to the equipment this way too.
A suggestion though, try to keep the descriptions for the new
equipment to one line so it does not wrap, it looks cleaner that way.
This is only a suggestion, some people like long item names, this is
only the opinion of the writer of this document.
#0
rp_npcs

B.Non-Player Characters (NPCs)

   Often Npcs enhance your rp. Incorporating them into your own emotes
can be not only entertaining, but a lot more realistic. If you're
playing a soldier in the Whitecloaks', unless that soldier has been
given leave from his post or he's snuck out of camp while off-duty, he
will not be alone. Other rpers should respect the NPCs being emoted
and treat them as they would treat the PC (Player Character) itself.
On the same token however, the rper with command over the few
Whitecloaks' with him, should be responsible as well. Do not abuse
the privilege given to you and go about, horribly slaying the
citizenry. Again, a common sense issue.
#0
rp_relatives

C. Relatives

   Another way to create a more in-depth environment is to work out
other players to be relatives of yours. It is a lot of fun and creates
a ton of interesting Roleplay. You should be careful though to work
out the history of your characters together so that you can incorporate
each other into your backgrounds appropriately. Come up with
interesting little snippets of things that have happened in the past,
everyone has a story or two about a relative... right? Create a
relationship that you both agree on. Do you guys hate each other? Are
you the best of friends? Does your younger sibling annoy you? Do you
hate your father? Those types of things make roleplaying with the other
player much more interesting. Just make sure that you work all this
out beforehand, it's not nice to spring something new on your relative.
#0
rp_rooms

D. Rooms/Houses

   Having a general room an inn is nice for awhile, but, some
characters like to expand upon that and actually have personalized
rooms and/or houses. Most Guilds offer a room for your character at
some stage, and you can simply send in a description that is
personalized to your character. Having a personalized space for your
character can tell your roleplay partners much about yourself,
especially with what is located in the description with items and
things. It is also a place where you can tell other Characters ICly
that they can find you, or leave you notes. This way, you can set up
interesting scenario's with someone, even if you rarely see them on at
the same time, you can roleplay via mail. If you wish to add something
more elaborate than a room, simply contact the Head Builder and the
Weaver with your request and a description of what are intending and
they will respond to you promptly.
#0
rp_jobs

E. Jobs

   A very good way to create both more Roleplay for your Character, as
well as substance, is to get a job IC'ly. Finding a noble, or a
merchant, or someone who needs a sword for hire is a good way to
establish yourself in circles about the mud. Just be careful to not
limit yourself to only RP'ing with that one person. It can be extremely
boring if they're not around much. Keeping yourself as open as possible
allows you to Roleplay with whomever comes your way. For instance, if
you get a job as a servant Noble, you're not serving 24/7, you are
allowed to have days off, or even be on errands for your Lord or Lady.
Use your imagination, it's free!
#0
rp_etiquette

Tips and Advice:

A. Roleplay Etiquette and Advice

   There are many rules of thumb, mostly unspoken ones, that
roleplayers generally follow. They will be elaborated on below, but
one warning, this is not a roleplay bible. This document is only as
informed as the person who writes it. Regardless, to the etiquette
and enough of my blathering.

1) Actions in an Emote: Although it is possible to execute more than
one action per emote, it would be advisable not to do this overmuch.
Think about the people you're rping with, put yourselves in their
shoes. If someone types out an eight line emote, which describes his
character having leaped multiple tall buildings at a single bound,
killed the Dark One and swam across the Aryth ocean, they're probably
not going to be looked upon favorably by their peers. This does not
mean that you should do numerous one line emotes which accomplish the
same task, it means, give your rp  partners an opportunity to respond
to your emote before you continue on in your rp. A general rule
to gauge such is allow everyone you are rping with to emote, before
you emote once more. You do not need to follow this rule in every
occasion. Say for example, you're having a conversation with someone
and whoever else is in the room, isn't doing anything to involve
his/herself in your rp, ignore them until they do involve themselves.
Just use common sense and courtesy when rping.

2) Closed Emotes or Actions: One of the major pet peeves for any
experienced rper, is someone who executes a closed emote.

  "George walks up to you and breaks your nose with a vicious blow to
   your face. Laughing, he leans over your prone body and spits in
   your face. 'Take that Darkfriend', he sneers derisively."

   This is a perfect example of a closed emote. You do not know if you
can break the guy's nose. You're taking away your opponent's ability
to respond to your action. Here's an improvement and what George should
do.

  "George growls deep in his chest, those chilly blue eyes flashing
   dangerously, before he steps nearer you, his balled fist whistling
   forward in an attempt to shatter your nose and send you sprawling
   to the ground."

   Leave your actions open for a response by your opponent. Sure, on
occasion, you're going to be faced with some goofball who thinks he
can avoid your blows, sidestep projectile weapons with ease, smoke
three Blademasters without breaking a sweat. Ignoring these people
would be advisable. Try and explain to them that they should respect
your wishes in rp and that their action is inappropriate for the scene
and if they don't listen, avoid them for a time until they learn how
to rp properly.

3) Supermen : There are few things more irritating on a rp game, than
someone, as mentioned above, who thinks he/she can blithely ignore your
actions or can simply set them aside without disturbing a hair. Please
avoid doing this. If someone executes a realistic action, respond with
a realistic action of your own. If someone steps up to you and tries
to lop your head off with his sword, respond by meeting the attack,
rather than leaping back ten feet so that the blow whistles through
the air where your body was four seconds ago and then leaping forward
through that space again and exploiting some weakness. Always keep in
mind that people are constantly moving. Because we aren't using true
VR technology for our game, we must rely upon our individual typing
speeds. As 1 and 2 touched on previously, be respectful of your fellow
rpers, respect their actions and respond to them accordingly and
realistically, not foolishly.

4) Realism: This is not so much necessary to know of before you begin
rping, but it will gain you more rp because you're 'with it' when you
rp. There are several types of realism we can address,  such as realism
by giving your character a personality that is not perfect, realism by
acknowledging the fact that it takes time to get anywhere, realism by
knowing your character is not Hercules and can not lift an entire
building. I know it is a difficult concept to think of 'realistic' RP
in a game based off of a book created by  some author, but, we're
assuming that most of the laws of our world are similar there (ie.
gravity does exist, a person is only so strong, a horse can only
travel so fast). When RP concerns magic such as the One Power, then
it is 'realistic' according to the laws that Robert Jordan made up
through writing his books (ie. male channelers can not grasp Saidar,
female channelers can not sense the spark in male channelers or see
them holding Saidin, not everyone is skilled in healing like the Kin
or the Yellow Ajah, and more).

   The personality of your character and realism. It is not wise to
rp a character who is drop dead gorgeous or handsome, with money coming
out of their ears, the intelligence to rival the best scholars, and
knowledge and cunning to defeat a Forsaken. Please roleplay your
character with flaws. We all have our shortcomings and our problems.
One of those old human truisms, no one's perfect, should be held to
like gospel when you're rping. If you're gorgeous, be not particularly
the brightest bulb in the box. If you're utterly smart, be an uncouth
bastard who doesn't have an incredibly high ability in social
interaction with others. If you're a scholar and know things no one
else does, like about the Forsaken or have some sort of secret dredged
up from some forgotten library, be arrogant and recluse. If you're
Mr. Moneybags, be condescending and superior in your power.

   At this point, some may say, well my character is just not like any
of that and that is probably true. Illustrated above is a guideline to
remember when one is thinking about making a character. You may be rich
but have spent the majority of your life learning humility from having
worked along side your common man. This is all possible, but you need
to remember that without a powerful influence coming into your
character's life to change their attitude, usually when they're outstanding 
at one thing, they'll have a horrible draw back in another.

   Balance is the name of the game. Be balanced and realistic with your
characters and not only will people enjoy rping with you and therefore
give you more rp, you will have more fun. Contrary to popular belief,
it's rather entertaining rping a flawed character.

   I'll digress a moment to speak of Rand. He's largely an untrusting
boy thrust into the shoes of a man who once ruled the majority of the
world and who, for 500 years, was acknowledged the preeminent power in
the Age of Legends. This has a profound effect on Rand. Not only does
he fall into the unwise trap of being arrogant in his power and
knowledge, he's stubborn and unyielding, unwilling to listen to other
points of view. He will need to pay the price for his folly and that
will create rp for his player and for those around him. Really, book
characters are just examples for people to follow or take knowledge
from. If you look at the various  personalities outlined in the novels,
it's a rare thing to find  someone who is perfectly balanced
perfection. Remember that when you rp and try it, it's quite
interesting to act out.
#0
rp_where

B. Where to find Roleplay

   Finding constant rp on any Mud, can be somewhat difficult. Some may
merely be idling or talking with friends or killing mobs (the non
player character mobiles in the game), but for those who wish to find
RP, there are a few tactics you can employ.

1) The majority of the rp that occurs on Fang, centers, at the moment
anyway, around the Andoran city of Caemlyn. The social center of
Caemlyn is the Oval Plaza, down, north and west from where you enter
from character creation. This Plaza often has RP occurring in it, from
merely idle IC chatter with others, to conflicts between the various
guilds that populate our game. If you wish to find rp, this is one of
the places you would want to start looking.

2) The various guilds have guild areas where the majority of their rp
occurs. For example, in the Rebel camp, the vast amount of RP that
occurs in the Rebel Sedai and Warders, is in Salidar, a small town in
Altara where they have made their stronghold. The White Tower, who
believe themselves to be the true Aes Sedai and the true movers and
shakers of the world's events, has a great deal of their RP occur in
Tar Valon. This is not to say that these are the only places one may rp
with Aes Sedai and Warders. In fact, many of these travel to Caemlyn
and the other populated cities we have built, to find different RP.
Thus these diverse groups, manage to intermingle with the mud as a
whole, both ICly and OOCly.

3) Caemlyn has quite a few hot spots of RP. The common rooms of the
various inns (such as the Half Moon Inn or the Golden Bowl), the
courtyards, the palace, the Andoran Manor are just a few spots to
mention. All one needs to do is seek out people in these populated
areas, connect with other characters ICly and OOCly, and move on from
there.
#0
rp_setup

C. How to set up Roleplay

   Setting up rp can be one of the most beneficial things you'll ever
learn on a mud. Finding people or setting up events through OOC
methods, often will net you a great deal of RP in both the areas of
expanding your experiences with the various guilds and giving your
character more depth, moings to talk about, in short, events and people
and IC happenings that occur, help to fill out the personality that
you've outlined in character generation.

1) Using Storytellers and Guildleaders: The Guildleaders (GLs) of
Dragon's Fang have all been selected for their abilities with creating
rp, being patient with people new to the game, solving disputes with
their guildees and with the people on the mud as a whole and finally,
for their common sense and down-to-earth attitudes. Sure, sometimes
you'll encounter the occasional bad apple, we can't all be perfect, but
for the most part, the Guildleaders and Storytellers (STs) we have on
Fang, are there for the express purpose of assisting you in having a
better rping experience. The GLs are people you can go to when you need
help setting up  RP. Lets say for the sake of argument, that you're
getting bored with the repetition, the same old, same old RP scene and
you want to find something new. Your GL is your contact. Go to them
with a suggestion for an event they can run or a scene they can set
up for you. Immortals aren't just immortals because they have the
skills above, they're there to use their skills. Ask them to help you
put something together and spark RP in your particular guild.

   Beyond the various GLs though, are your Storytellers. These people
are immed because they've proven to the Storyguide, the head of the
department, that they know how to RP, know how to set up a quick,
relaxing scene of RP,ultimately, know how to craft long-running plot, a
series of interconnected events which allows for the creation of
RP for a significant amount of time. Again, just like the GLs, the STs
are there to help you make your time on Fang enjoyable. However, if you
aren't enjoying the string of scenes a Storyteller offers, because you
either just don't like it or it doesn't really suit you, you are more
than welcome to ask for something specifically for you and your
friends.

   If there's something you especially want, tell us. Don't be shy
about it. The GLs and STs work closely together, in an attempt to bring
you a fun RPing environment, but you can help us by telling us and
suggesting to us, events, scenes and plots, that will be enjoyed by
all.

2) The Town Crier: The town Crier has been set up in various locations
throughout the Mud, in hopes that his database of IC stories will be
used and read by everyone playing Dragon's Fang. He holds the entire
history of the Mud, the RP that has occurred on Fang for the past four
odd years and that hasn't been illustrated in the novels already. If
you think something else should be added. Maybe you've RPed in an event
that you think the Storytellers and especially the rest of the Mud,
should know about. Tell the Storyguide, because  ultimately, its his
responsibility to keep the Crier up-to-date. It can be an excellent way
of having your RP showcased and at the same time, giving RP to others
as well.

3) The Mail System: The mail system, is both IC and OOC in nature. It
can help a great deal in setting up RP. There will be additions to it
in the very near future, which will allow for more diversity and
flexibility in this system, but for now, please use it to set up times
to RP with your friends or people you think you would RP with. Lets say
that you're a Child of the Light and you've spotted an Aiel that you
think needs a beat down. Send him/her off a mail about setting up a
time to RP and your wish to have a scene with them. This doesn't mean
you need to plan out the RP, just that it helps the flow of
commmunication and helps you find more and more RP, which after all, is
the goal.

   The mail system can also be an IC form of communication. Perhaps
you're a soldier, writing a report for your Captain or a Noblewoman,
writing to your husband at war, or maybe you're sending encrypted
correspondence to a fellow player of Daes Dae'mar.  Whatever the
particular situation, you can utilize the mail system for this purpose
as well and ultimately, communication.
#0
rp_basic


Beginning Roleplay including Terms/Terminology:

A. What is IC versus OOC? What is RP?

   Let's start by first defining the terms. IC is short for 'In
Character', OOC is short for 'Out of Character', and RP is shorthand for
'Roleplay'. To go IC in Dragon's Fang, it is a simple toggle command in
which you type 'goic'. To go OOC, you type 'goooc'. When a person
roleplay's, they are expected to always be IC, OOC is for when you are
just talking or leveling your character to make them more powerful
codewise. Being IC means that you are ready for any roleplay that might
just show up your way, regardless of the consequences.

   For those of you who do not know what roleplay is exactly, the best
way I can describe it is acting. A Character is created, by you the
player. All aspects of the Character is thought up, the background
history, looks, merits/flaws and more. When the player goes IC, they
place themselves into the Character and act as that Character would in
the situations that are presented to them in the Wheel of Time World,
using Emotes and Poses. This leads us to our next topic...
#0
rp_emotebasic

B. What is an Emote?

   An emote itself is how one expresses oneself in roleplay on a mud. It
is not uncommon for this command to be supplemented by a pose command
which does similar to emote, only allows you to describe an action
without emote's limitations. An example if your character's name was
George:

** You typed: emote pours a glass of deep red wine into a gold-chased
goblet, swirling the rich alcoholic-laced liquid with a gentle finger.

** Your audience would see:
George pours a glass of deep red wine into a gold-chased goblet,
swirling the rich alcoholic-laced liquid with a gentle finger.

   Essentially, when you type out an emote, if you substitute the word
emote for the name of your character, that is what the others in the
room with you, will see. The same goes for pose, only the name of your
character doesn't show up in the action unless you type it out manually.
An example of pose is:

** You typed: pose Relaxing into a plush, cushioned chair, George lifts
his feet up to rest upon the mahogany coffee table before him, his eyes
closing to half-slits as his deep blue eyes languidly regard the room at
large.

** Your audience would see:
Relaxing into a plush, cushioned chair, George lifts his feet up to rest
upon the mahogany coffee table before him, his eyes closing to
half-slits as his deep blue eyes languidly regard the room at large.

   So beyond the basic mechanics of how to emote, it is an action that
your character performs. They are broadcast to the room that you are
located in, no further, unless there are some special commands given to
a particular guild, to allow for that.

   To describe how one roleplays, it would probably be easiest to tell
you to simply flip open a book and read a few pages of character
interaction. None of us are writers of repute and thus our emotes are
largely going to be inferior than what you see in a novel. This also
doesn't mean you should simply copy what you see, but an emote is
generally something you would find in a novel, especially in the ways
they are written.

   Descriptiveness in emotes is absolutely key. Don't pump out one
liners and wait the minute or two for your rp partner to eloquently
describe, in four lines, what his/her own character is doing. Again,
remember respect for your fellow rper. Put some effort, not only in
describing what others would see coming from your character in facial
features, body language and voice inflection, but do as well as you can
do with grammar and spelling, so that it isn't a pain for anyone to rp
with you. Some may think this harsh and for some, English is definitely
not your primary language. That is totally understandable and you are
certainly not going to be ridiculed for misplacing a tense or an
adjective. Do the best you can, that's all one can ask another to do.
#0
rp_emoteinclude 

C. What should an Emote include

   An Emote should include as much as possible to describe the situation
as clearly as possible to your audience (the people you are roleplaying
with, or simply just others who are watching). I've thought up a few
things that would be extremely nice to have included in an emote, those
include:

1) Where your Character is located in the area.
   Describe where your character is standing so others would know. If
you're near someone, leaning against a tree, then they would probably
like to know that. You can emote specifics, such as,

  "George walks into the area, he pauses next to the tall building in
   the distance as he looks around searching for someone."

Or, you can place yourself relative to another person, such as,

  "George walks into the area, he pauses just behind and slightly to the
   right of Jill as he looks around, searching for someone."

   You can be more descriptive than this easily, this is merely an
example of putting location into an emote.

2) Movements your Character is doing.
   Another really nice thing to include in an emote is what exactly your
character is doing. Your character can be doing anything at any time,
simple things included. A brush of a pant leg to get some dirt off,
hands running through hair, hands balled into fists with the knuckles
white from the tension, walking towards someone with a hand resting on a
sword hilt, kicking dirt off your boots, etc. It can really include
anything. For example, let's continue the emote we started above with
location.

  "George walks into the area, he pauses just behind and slightly to the
   right of Jill as he looks around, searching for someone. He brings up
   a calloused hand to run through his hair as his eyes move from one
   person in the area to the next."

   Of course, the portion of 'as he looks around' and 'walks into the
area', are also movements, I simply added more movements to the emote.
Just a small note here, an emote does not have to just be one sentence.
You don't have to have this huge run-on sentence to describe everything
you want to describe. More than one sentence is allowed in an emote, as
well as easier to understand because it is usually more clear.

3) Facial expressions and what your Character is feeling.
   A common mistake for beginning Roleplayers is to type out emotions in
an emote in an attempt to have the character's feelings come across. I
admit, it is often very difficult to walk the fine line of trying to
come across as feeling this way in a character versus simply and
sometimes inadvertently just telling your audience. You should remember
though, that in reality, unless someone is psychic, they can't really
tell what your emotions are except through signs. We can do that in
Roleplay though, describe the signs of what your character is feeling.
Good signs can be anything from facial expressions, physical actions, a
look in the eye, to even simply words. Let's look at two examples of the
dos and don'ts.

Don't:
  "George walks into the area, he pauses just behind and slightly to the
   right of Jill as he looks around, searching for someone. He brings up
   a calloused hand to run through his hair as his eyes move from one
   person in the area to the next. He wonders if anyone has seen his
   brother, he hasn't seen him in weeks and is worried for him."

   Can you see the mistakes in that last Sentence? For one, no one can
read his mind, and for another, unless someone is psychic, they can't
tell (or shouldn't be able to tell) that George is worried. A good
correction of this would be:

Do:
  "George walks into the area, he pauses just behind and slightly to the
   right of Jill as he looks around, searching for someone. He brings up
   a calloused hand to run through his hair as his eyes move from one
   person in the area to the next. With a worried expression crossing
   his face he sighs and then turns to Jill, asking, "Have you seen my
   brother? His name is Bob."

   With this correction, you get the same feeling coming across, yet
IC'ly a person can tell with the signs, as well as words, instead of
reading the person's mind.

4) What you are saying and to whom.
   The reason for Roleplaying is to interact with others, right? One of
the best ways to interact is through speech. So, most emotes contain
someone saying something to another. Another Tip I can give is to make
sure you put specific names if there is more than one other person in
the room. If you type the emote with a question of 'asks you', then the
three other people in the room aren't quite clear on exactly who you are
speaking to. Look at the corrected emote above. George turned to Jill
and asked her a question.

   You can also add tones and any inflections or even an accent when
speaking to someone. It's quite fun and adds some variety to your
character. An example could be:

  "With a worried expression crossing his face, George sighs and then
   turns to Jill. He asks with a sharply clipped accent, "Be you seeing
   muh Broth'r? He be named Bob."

   Of course, this example is merely that, an example. There are much
better emotes than this above, and I'm sure you'll experience them in
some RP.

5) Anything amiss.
   Another good thing to include in an emote is if anything is different
than the 'norm'. The norm being your description, or if you're any
different than the last time you roleplayed with that person. If you got
your hair cut and haven't had time to change your description, that'd be
a good thing to add. If you got hurt in a fight and are limping, or have
this huge bandage that causes your arm to be pinned to your chest would
both be excellent things to add as well. The rule is, whatever you want
someone to see or notice about you, you should put something in a pose
or emote that they can icly view.
#0
rp_whatfirst

D. What do you do when you first enter a room/area?

   One of the first things you should do before even emoting when you
enter a room/area is to look at the doings and people's descriptions (if
you haven't already read them recently). A doing is a command on
Dragon's Fang that is used to add a dialog behind a person's name that
tells everyone in the room what this person is doing at this point,
where they are at, and anything else the player wants to let others
know. To create a doing, all one would type is:

** doing leaning against a tree, smoking a pipe.

When a person looked in the room, they would see:

** George is leaning against a tree, smoking a pipe.

Notice that I deliberately left out the is when typing in the doing
statement. The program on the game automatically adds it for you.

   When reading the doings of people in the room, you should try to
establish where everyone is located. If you can't do this by reading
doings' and listening to one emote, then sending the person a tell,
asking them is also a way to find out. Once figuring out where everyone
is situated, try to get a semi-decent understanding of what's going on,
and if anything dramatic isgoing on at the moment.

   Once you have an impression of where people are located and
approximately what they're doing (this shouldn't take more than a minute
or two), the next step is to emote your entrance using the guidelines
above and have fun!
#0
rp_what

Starting Out - Character Creation:

   When you're just starting out, there are several major factors you
should keep in mind when creating a character. These factors include
the who, what, where, why and how questions. These are only a few
questions one can come up with when thinking about a new Character:
Who are you? What is your personality? What do you want to be able to
do? Where are you from? Why are you the way you are? How do you do the
things you do?

A.  What to keep in mind when thinking up a Character

1)  Who are you?
   So, who are you? What is your name? What do you want to look like?
Do you have family and friends? Where are they now? Do you have a
horse? A dog? You can come up with many, many things to answer when
thinking up answers to the Who am I question. I would suggest getting
only as detailed as you feel comfortable, because you'll have to
remember all these details later in order to Roleplay your character.

2)  Where is the Character From?
   This question is another rather obvious one. Answer it, then
try to expand on it. Where did you grow up? Did you move? Did you
have friends left behind? Did you know the area well? What morals
were instilled into your character because of where you grew up?

   These are just a few more questions you can answer to develop
your Character more.

3)  What type of Character do you want?
   This is a rather important question. Do you want your character to
be a fighter? A thinker? A lover? A thief? A wimp? A lord? lady? This
will help you in building your background if you know what type you
want to be.

4)  What type of Personality do you want your Character to have?
   Personality is rather important for any Character, especially if you
want to have 'depth'. Human beings are complex creatures, this means
you don't just have to always display one emotion. Your character could
be very short tempered and easy to peeve off, but, quickly satiated by
a honeycake.. Your Character could be really shy, or really flirty, or
flirty when they don't like someone and shy when they do. Or, your
Character could have an immense hatred for blondes, or for some obscure
reason be so soft-hearted they want to help any injured animal they
cross. Try to think up little quirks your Character has, it makes
things more interesting for both you and your Roleplay partners.

    Remember though, that whatever you think up here, you should think
up a reason why your Character is this way.. did something bad happen?
Nothing bad ever happened so your Character is trusting? A blonde broke
your heart? Only blondes broke your heart? Your father was a blonde and
beat you when you were younger? There's always something interesting to
put into a background to explain the reasons why.

5)  What Merits or Flaws does your Character have?
   This goes hand in hand with personality. Your Character could be
kind hearted, or cold hearted, or really easy to anger, or just plain
apathetic. The more developed your character is, the more interested
and multi-faceted they will be to Roleplay. Other types of merits and
flaws could be the physical and mental. Does your character only have
one eye? How did that happen? Does your Character have a limp? How? Is
your Character really strong? Do they work out? Lift heavy objects
daily? Is your Character really weak? Is your Character mentally
unstable and prone to go off at the slightest noise, or burst out
crying? There are many, many things you can think of. Be creative, you
have the freedom to do so.

6)  What do you want your Character to look like?
   What did your parents look like? Do you take after them? Your
grandparents? Is your Character tall, short, wide, skinny, weak, pale,
dark.. what?
#0
rp_background


B.  Creating a Good Background

   In creating a good background, including everything from the
questions above is a major plus. If you have given your Character a
merit, explain how. If your Character knows how to do something,
explain when and where they learned, how long it took to learn, and
who taught them. The more detailed the better. Explaining where you
are from, things about your family, things about the place you grew up
at, little stories from your past that made you the way you are today
(personality)... all this makes up your background, and answering the
Who, What, Why, When, Where, How is a good way to make sure you cover
your bases.
#0
rp_description

C.  Creating a Good Description

   One of the most important things about rping on a game such as ours,
is a good, solid workable description. You may then ask, "What's a
good, solid, workable description?" A proper description is one that
eloquently describes your character's form. In the description, you
should outline what kinds of clothing are being worn; what is visible
through the clothing; what parts of your character's body is bare
skin; what peculiar objects, if any, your character is carrying; any
distinctive markings such as scars, tattoos, or any other deformities
or outstanding qualities one might see at a glance. Basically, what
you're doing is taking a  snapshot of your character and describing
that snapshot. Do not put any actions in the description, remember that 
snapshot is a still-image photo and that you're not moving, smiling
or grinning like a fool or otherwise in a good or bad mood. You can
describe the moods common to your character, their general disposition,
but remember that anything specific should appear in your emotes,
rather than in your description. Here are some examples to help you
along, both from the Wheel of Time universe and from modern day
society.

Example 1:   Long red tresses frame a plain face, a strong chin and
two deep-set emerald green eyes, perhaps the only features one might
call beautiful or even handsome. A scar runs from his left ear, down to
his chin, a long, almost angry slash as if some clawed thing had raked
him in the night. His 6-2, perhaps 200 pound form is garbed in shirt
and jeans of a uniform blue, the fabric rather faded as it clings to
his muscled body. A very worn leather flight jacket has been pulled
across his broad shoulders, left open to reveal a small silver chain
which hangs down on to his chest, oft fingered by one of his calloused
hands. All in all, he has an air of seclusion about him, introspective
if you will, drawn into himself.

Example 2:   Eyes like deep brown unreadable stones, stare out of a
hardened, chiselled face with firm chin, broad mouth, high cheek bones
and shoulder length brown hair that is brushed back from his face, but
whose strands from time to time, fall into his eyes and obscure vision.
His roughly six foot tall frame, is well-muscled and clad in finely
woven wool tunic and breeches of a deep green, a roaring lion
emblazoned upon the left of his tunic, a rose wrapped sword upon the
right. A cloak of equally fine wool, is slung across his shoulder, the
fabric in the same dark hew as his other clothing. His hands are all
that is bare except his face, the thick fingers and palms covered in
thick callouses created by the wielding of a sword, a ring of high
quality gold, encircling his right ring finger. Despite his hard and
unyielding appearance, a light shines in his eyes, a rediscovered joy
that is ever-present beneath his outwardly cold bearing.

Example 3:   Prim is this small figure, barely reaching 5' 2". A
slender form draped in a silken dress of the softest blue. Her hair, a
dark brown is pulled back almost extremely, into a proficient bun,
sometimes a ponytail at the base of her neck, and other times into a
long braid... but always back, away from her face and eyes. Her
features are angular, her cheekbones high and looking back from her
ever so pale blue eyes, a hawks look. Her angular face, small, pointy
nose and sharp eyes give her the distinct similarity to a hawk or
predatory bird. She often walks softly, purposefully, and almost every
single one of her actions carefully planned out, even folding her hands
before her. She has a look of extreme intelligence, and a streak of
gray can be seen on her left temple, near her bangs. Her face is
smooth, pale as porcelain and completely ageless.
#0
proposal

The following is a document containing all the important factors
about channeling that one may wish to keep in mind, while
roleplaying. Please note that these are book referenced facts and
have been simply compiled, in hopes that they will be read,
thought of and considered when one roleplays a character of this
nature.

Help proposal1: A summary of the Five Flows.
Help proposal2: An analysis of Saidin and Saidar, how they contrast.
Help proposal3: Comparing male and female strengths.
Help proposal4: Analysis of weaving.
Help proposal5: The dangers of the One Power.


Conclusion: While the Power is something that only Robert Jordan
knows the ins and outs of, we can make many educated guesses in
hopes of roleplaying it properly. Above all these concepts and
rules though, is the need for common sense. If you, the player,
keep in mind the fact that you are not god, but a mortal with
merits and flaws, abilities and drawbacks, you will be able to rp
a very successful Channeler. It is always entertaining to play a
character who can kill anyone, do anything, but it will simply
lead to problems in a multi-user environment.
#0
proposal1
     
The Five flows: Air, Water, Earth, Spirit and Fire are all
components of the One Power.

  Air: The most often used flow and one of the simplest. It is a
flow designed to manipulate tangible objects, by using the ever-
present air around us, hardening it into walls, wrapping it
around objects or people, creating platforms to walk upon,
whatever the case may be, Air on its own, is simply the
manipulation of the plain oxygen and Nitrogen mix we live and
breathe.

  Water: Unlike Air, this flow is not simply at hand at all
times. It is drawn from the moisture-laden air and from the
clouds in the sky or from bodies of nearby water but unlike Air,
it is not always surrounding us and easily accessible. For
example, if one wished to use Water and Fire to create a
lightning bolt or storm, one must set the conditions for using
the Water element by moving clouds into the proper position and
then weaving the lightning, using the cloud's water content as
the catalyst for the electricity. Otherwise, Water like Air,
Spirit and Fire, is a flow predominantly used in healing.

  Spirit: This is perhaps the most unusual and complex element of
the One Power. Largely used for weaves of creation or for the
mind, this flow allows the Channeler to create illusions, use
Compulsion, change the shape and state of animate and inanimate
objects, to create something out of nothing. Examples of
predominantly Spirit-woven weaves are dreaming traps, light-woven
invisibility, Shielding, severing and Aes Sedai bonding.

  Fire: Much like Air and Water, this flow is around us at all
times. It is presumed, though not confirmed by any known source,
that simply applying the laws of physics will explain much of how
these flows work together. For example, if you increase the pace
of atoms in air, you create heat. If you do this at a rapid
enough rate, you will create a tangible weave of fire. Therefore,
using Air and Fire, you are able to not only set the conditions
for a fireball, but are able to use the air to shape the fire and
direct it to its intended target. Otherwise, this component of
the One Power, is simple, much like air and Water.

  Earth: Like fire, this flow is simply elements of the ground we
stand upon or bits of the air, drawn out to form hardened pieces
of rock or dirt. It is shown to us in The Great Hunt, from
Egwene's vague description of her Ore-finding talent, that Earth
is perhaps more complex than fire, Air or Water, in that it
allows one to delve into the earth and search for elements lying
therein, such as metals in her case. How this would be done, is
simply speculation, but perhaps this is an example of the more
magical, fictional, side of the One Power, rather than the
previously illustrated scientific part.

  Having described the simple elements of the One Power in their
component parts, the next step is to determine how they work
together. Singly, the flows will do little but their obvious
purpose, like for example, using simple flows of Air as a wrap to
halt the motion of an object or to lift it, or otherwise
manipulate it. Working in tangent however, is an entirely
different story. Weaves woven of Air, Water and Spirit for
example, has been the traditional method of Aes Sedai healing.
Using Spirit and combining that with Air and Water, you set the
conditions for the weave to heal by how you weave it and then you
simply allow it to run its intended course. 
#0
proposal2

Saidin and Saidar: The two halves of the One Power are as
different as men and women, a direct corilation in fact. Saidin
is a male characterized power, a strong, unyielding, war-like
force that needs to be directed, not listened to. It is a weapon
of destruction or healing, but a weapon all the same,. Like
Saidar however, Saidin is still a sweet, intoxicating power. For
all of its war-like struggle for freedom from its holder, once
guided, Saidin is a powerful tool for good or evil. A quote from
the novels concerning holding Saidin: "That fight that told a man
he was alive." This is exactly what Saidin is. When going into
the Void, one pushes all emotion aside, in exchange for calmness
and serenity. Only then, is one able to dominate and control
Saidin and force it to submit to the will of the wielder. When
that person manages to control Saidin, they feel everything
sharper, smells, sight, hearing, taste, everything is amplified
quite significantly. Yet, there is a difference. Wrapped in the
void, one can not simply feel these enhancements and truly
understand them. It is best described as if everything was
clearer, yet as if you were riding in the back of someone else's
mind, an intimate observer but only an observer, feeling it
second hand, not the immediacy of total contact.
  Saidar, on the other hand, is quite different. Saidar is an
embracing of power, an opening up, an envelopping, immercing, in
the strength that is the female half of the True Source. Holding
Saidar is a submission to a sweet, glorious and addictive
superior power. Once submitting to this power, the wielder is in
total command of Saidar, yee, the threat of overdrawing the
Source is even moreso than wielders of Saidin. The sweet,
intoxicating, glory of Saidar can be so overwhelming if drawn in
vast amounts, that only an extreme will of iron, combined with
long years of wielding Saidar, can prevent the woman from simply
drawing the essence into her and burning herself out. This is why
Aes Sedai train their charges so agonizingly slow, for increasing
the pace of their training, also increases the chance of simply
cutting oneself off from the very glorious power they are trying
to draw more of. 
#0
proposal3

Comparing male and female strengths: this has ever been a
contencious issue whenever male channelers contact wfemale ones.
Male channelers are almost invariably stronger than female
channelers on a one-on-one level. Whether simply blessed with the
ability to grasp more sheer volume of the One Power or whether
this is a characteristic difference between Saidin and Saidar, is
unknown, yet it is clearly stated that unless a very powerful
woman contacts a weaker male, the male will be stronger than the
woman. For example, women sent to shield Rand or many of the
other stronger false Dragons, would have been in the more
powerful ranks of the Aes Sedai. yet it is clearly written that
six of these Aes Sedai are not a match for one such False Dragon.
Having said that, your average male channeler who is perhaps less
than half the strength of Rand or Logain or any of the stronger
Forsaken, would only be able to handle two or three of these Aes
Sedai at the very most and most likely with a tremendous amount
of risk involved in the undertaking. 
  However, men cannot link together with other men unless they
have women to support the link. this has always been the
counterbalancing factor when  conflicts between male and female
channelers arise. Women are able to link together, to a daunting
number of thirteen, while men, unless they have a female to link
with, cannot link with a single other man. Thus, when women
approach men to gentle them or capture them, a link of such
numbers or at least something more than six or seven Aes Sedai,
is required to be assured of the capture and in overpowering the
man.
#0
proposal4

Weaving: While much of this area of channeling lies in the realm
of fiction and assumed action, there are parts of the mechanics
of weaving, described in various places throughout the novels.
The main point that is brought up time and time again is one's
ability in a particular flow, amplifying the effectiveness of the
woven weave. For example, Elayne in book four, while journeying
to Tanchico, has an opportunity to observe a Windfinder at work
on the Seafolk vessel she is using to travel from Tear to
Tarabon. While Elayne could in theory, perform the weaves that
the Windfinder executed with such skill, she stated that she
could not possibly be able to affect a tenth of the weather the
Windfinder was able to. Elayne is perhaps one of the top ten
female Channelers living in the current world in terms of
potential and raw power, while the Windfinder was a great deal
weaker than the Daughter-heir. 
  This situation yields much information in
regards to the mechanics of channeling. Mainly, if a Channeler is
shown how to weave something and is given practice with weaving
the displayed weave, they not only become more adept in the
weave, their strength in the particular flow also increases.
While this may seem like the channeler may simply keep practicing
and becoming a super Channeler, this is not the case. Perhaps the
analogy of a muscle would be appropriate to describe this
concept. If one does not use their muscles, they atrophy and
weaken and shrink, to the point where one cannot perform tasks
one used to be able to do with ease. However, if one uses their
muscles often, exercises them, tests them and stretches them to
the limit, one becomes stronger until they have reached their
physiological limit.
  So it is with Weaving and perhaps, gives insight into why the
older Aes sedai and Wise Ones, are often a great deal more adept
in the arts of channeling, than the younger channelers, save of
course, the notable exceptions outlined in the books.
  One last point on Weaving. It is often stated that a channeler
is shaped by who he or she is taught by. For example, if a woman
is shown the fireball weave by her Aes sedai teacher, and said
teacher flings out her arm to release the fireball, that is
ingrained into how the weave is woven for the student. The
student will have to make the arm gesture to complete the weave
or otherwise, it will not run its proper course.
  This also shows why the Age of Legends produced so many
talented Channelers, with many diverse and complicated skills.
They were able to teach their students how to channel and what to
channel, without also passing on the flaws of the teacher to the
pupil. 
#0
proposal5

Dangers of Channeling: Channeling is a very dangerous, very risky
process without any sort of formal training. Even Rand al'Thor,
the absolute cream of the crop where the One Power is concerned,
is lost and left floundering in regards to Saidin, until he is
able to cut Asmodean off from the Dark One and force the former
Forsaken to show him the pitfalls of the True Source. Before this
point, he ran the risk, every time he grasped Saidin, if he could
grasp it in the first place, of losing control of the battle with
Saidin and simply drawing too much power to handle without having
it burn his mind away. 
  What one must keep in mind in roleplay is simply this. Your
character must have formal training in the One Power before he or
she can do much beyond lighting a candle. Even if this
hypothetical character attempted to light the candle, half the
time they would fail to reach the One Power and the rest of the
time, they would not be able to focus the Power enough to perform
the designed task. Not only does one not know how to wield the
One Power without training, they simply do not know how to reach
it and if they were able to reach it, they are more apt to
destroy themselves than do anything useful.
#0
bookie-application
If you wish to obtain a Book Character, you must complete the following
and send it to the appropriate Guildleader or to the Storyguide if the
bookie is not in a guild, via mudmail or e-mail or whichever medium they
deem expedient.

1) What ooc qualifications do you have to play this character?
2) Why do you want to play this character?
3) Construct a description that you would use for this character.
4) Describe, in brief, what the character has done in the series.
5) List notable merits and flaws pertaining to the character.
6) Describe your rp plans for the character.
7) Describe what you wish to accomplish with the character.
8) How much time per week can you devote to playing this character?

Any other questions, please see the Storyguide and he can help you further.
#0
SKIM SKIMMING
Very similar to Gating, this technique of travelling is slower
but it allows one to move from point A, to point B, without
having to know your starting point intimately. Fashioning a gate
that carries you into a void, you use a platform to carry you to
your destination, which takes moments or seconds, depending on
where you are travelling in the world. When you reach your
destination, another Gateway will open, allowing you to exit the
void, and appear at the intended target. 

SEE ALSO: Gate
#0
OBSCENE

Obscene is a channel for only the strong-minded. If you want to hear
your ears burn, have your eyes pop, or just plain be offensive,
turn it on. It starts off for all new players, and if you prefer
the cleaner side of things, it is suggested you keep it off. Most
things are fair game on the channel, and below is a definition of
what is not. With the existence of this, remind yourself again
that the other channels, including GDT, TT, and all guild channels
are to stay clean.

Usage:     Obscene <message>
Toggling:  noobscene

Yes, this channel's definition is one without policy. Yet in the
spirit of not seriously offending anyone, some ground rules need
to be laid. Note that this channel is very much a privilage; you
can curse and cuss on it all you want, but if anyone truly derives
anger or hurt from it, it is gone. Simply stating, do not bring
heavy flames to the channel. It is fine if they stay somewhat
controlled, but when a mortal or an immortal's name is being thrown
around and accused, that has crossed the line. We all like to flame
from time to time when ticked off, but if you really have a problem
with someone, there are other ways to handle it. Secondly, and
finally, do not have sex on the channel. Do not write paragraphs,
lines, quotes, or anything else having to do with the act. You can
allude to it, you can brag about yourself (not that anyone will
believe you), but do not start making examples of it. That should
stay private. Otherwise, have fun with the channel, and remember
that you can always turn it off.
#0
"AES SEDAI"

   3000 years ago when the Breaking of the World shattered the known
lands and scattered peoples, the channelers of that time, called 
Aes Sedai (the Servants of All in the Old Tongue) came to be
all that stood between success and failure for the light against
the Shadow. 
   In the act of freeing the lands from the Shadow's impending
domination, the male Aes Sedai received a crippling blow from the
Dark One to their abilities, every last one of them eventually driven
to madness through their very link to the source of their power;
thus when we speak of Aes Sedai since we refer to women who can
channel the female half of the True Source, from which the Aes Sedai's
power is drawn in the form of the One Power. This can be a fearsome weapon
in their hands, though the strength of the abilities varies from 
one person to the other.
  The title of the Aes Sedai is bestowed by either the Rebel
Tower, a group who felt that the White Tower's policies were
unjust, and by the White Tower, who has trained women to channel
for generations. 
  Blamed for the Breaking of the World despite what they did to
stop the Shadow, they are not trusted by the general population
and yet few rulers go without an Aes Sedai advisor. Their
knowledge is unparalleled but for what use they put that
knowledge is unclear to all but their own kind.

\c01SEE ALSO:\c00\c03 TOWER SEDAI, REBEL SEDAI, AJAH\c00
#0
ENHANCE

  Seeking to improve their importance and prestige across the
lands, Craftsmen managed to develop a method of improving the
armor of a warrior. Using a technique known only to themselves,
they return pieces of armor to the customer improved many times
over.
  Beware that some metals or special substances of which armor is
made, cannot be improved by these skilled smiths.
The Enhance skill is a guildskill, known only to Aiel Blacksmiths
and the Traveling People (Tinkers). It is used on a weapon to
increase its damage roll, or on armor to improve its absorbance
and AC.
#0
WOLFNAME

   The wolfkin refer to each other not by their human names, but
with a name chosen that is special to each.
   You can only choose that name once in a lifetime; if it needs
to be changed for some reason, only an Immortal can set that for
you, so choose it carefully!
   Before his name among the wolfkin has been chosen, that person's
projected thoughts and emotions will be barely more than whispers
in the night - sooner or later he has to lay claim to a name.
   The command is "\c03wolfname <name>\c00".
   
See Also: Wolfkin, Wolftalk, Wolfdream, WKGuild
#0
TOOL
  In times past, there have been periods when the great smiths of
the lands have not been sought out to perform their trade.
Seeking to find another method of drawing customers, the
Craftsmen drew together for a great council and
after that meeting was completed, many new inventions had been
made.
  Chiefly among these new ways of earning coin, was the skill
of Tooling. Using new alloys and other secrets known only by 
these smiths, they were able to change the appearence of almost
any object, save that most mysterious of alloys, Heartstone. 
  Finding someone to perform this task is rare but if you stumble
across a smith with talent, prepare to hand over a fee for the
service.

See also: CRAFTSMAN
#0
SEEKING SEEKER
Usage: seeking <guild name>
       seeking off
       seeking

   With this command, an unguilded character may declare his/her
intention to enlist into the ranks of any guild; it is not a
permanent decision, you can turn off seeking at any time or
seek another guild.
   Any guilded character can type \c01seeking\c00 without an
argument to obtain a listing of all the characters seeking
his/her guild, along with any sponsors.
   \c01Warning:\c00 If you stop seeking, or seek another guild you
will lose all the sponsors you may currently have.
  
\c01SEE ALSO:\c00 \c03sponsor\c00
#0
SPONSOR
Usage: sponsor <name>

   Any guilded character authorized by his/her Guildleader(s) 
may sponsor a "seeker" (a person wanting to join the same guild), 
by typing "\c02sponsor <person's name>\c00".
   After that, any member of the guild may type "\c02seeking\c00" to
get a list of all the characters seeking the guild along with 
the names of any sponsors they have.
   A seeker never sees who is sponsoring him or her; but in the
score sheet it is possible to see the number of sponsorships
they currently have.

\c01SEE ALSO:\c00 \c03seeking\c00
#0
CAEMLYN ANDOR DIRECTIONS LOST


Caemlyn was built to be as IC as possible, and while not all
of its descriptions are IC (yet), the layout is. Each gate is
in its proper place; there are 5 outer gates and two gates to
the Inner City. The Oval Plaze is at the foot of the Andoran
Royal Palace, and each road which is supposed to be in Caemlyn
according to the books thus far, is. 
 
This makes Caemlyn a wonderful place in which to roleplay.
It can also make Caemlyn extremely confusing. Anyone who has
ever studied the maps of Caemlyn from the Wheel of Time books
knows that Caemlyn is very oddly-shaped, with several distinct
"neighborhoods" of twisting, maze-ish streets. Thankfully,
here on Dragon's Fang, Caemlyn is scaled down to a reasonable
size. So, the streets are slightly less like mazes than they
appear to be in the books. But they are not all straight and
simple, and the helpfiles are designed to help anyone find
their way around the city.  
 
Each street in Caemlyn has its own helpfile. Study them as
you walk through Caemlyn. Each helpfile gives directions to
the oval plaza and describes where that street is in relation
to other streets. Here is a list of Caemlyn's streets, in
alphabetical order:
 
\c10Arrow Street
Bounty Crescent\c03**\c10
Counselor Boulevard\c03**\c10
Crown Boulevard\c03**\c10
East Gate Road**
Gate Roads\c03**\c00 (this entry describes all the gate roads and their
            relation to each other - "HELP GATEROADS")
\c10Ilyeras Street
Jadeflower Lane
Kenurae Street
Lion Avenue
Nerasis Road
North Gate Road\c03**\c10
Nyerin Lane
Oakseed Avenue
Palace Circle\c03**\c10
Park Circle
Protosa Lane
Queen's Circle\c03**\c10
Raesane Boulevard
Ryslede Street
Rose Avenue
Saiye Lane
Serafal Avenue
Silkfeather Lane
Slivera Boulevard
South Gate Road\c03**\c10
Tal'isani Road\c03**\c10
Twilight Arcade\c03**\c10
West Gate Road\c03**\c00
  
  
\c03**\c00 Note: this indicates a main road.
  
\c08When you use these helpfiles, do not type in the full
name of the road\c00. For example, type simply "\c14HELP RAESANE\c00"
rather than "Help Raesane Boulevard". 
 
In addition to these helpfiles, there are signs posted at
major intersections. Type look sign to read them. Also,
anyone wishing to have a map of Caemlyn may purchase one
at \c03The Hunted Horn Inn \c00in Illian, or e-mail Alishya at
brookes@princeton.edu.
