COUNCIL
A Council of 3 imms has been formed to help uphold and
enforce the \c03Policy \c00(type '\c03policy\c00'), and to act as
a mediator between IC and OOC problems or issues.

Some examples that would fall into our category include, but are
not limited to, the following:

- *Any* issue that involves the \c03Policy \c00(type '\c03policy\c00'). This
  includes multiplaying, harrassment, and OOC stealing and tooling.

- IC conflicts such as determining the winner of a roleplay fight.

- OOC conflicts such as using OOC info or bug abuse.

There are numerous conflicts/issues/problems/arguments that
should be brought to our attention. Mail us with the issue and we
will question both sides before making a decision.

If you are unsure whether you should bring the issue to us, do
the safe thing and just do it; we are here to help.

Please send a tell or mail to any or all Council members with
your questions/conflicts/issues. Like I stated earlier, we are
here to help.

The current Councilors are: \c03Geoffrey, Valaire, Reiten\c00
#0
DAES DAE'MAR GAME

Otherwise known as the Great Game of Houses or simply as the Great Game 
and in the Old Tongue, Daes Dae'mar.  It is the scheming, plots and 
manipulations for advantage by noble Houses.  Great value is given to 
subtlety, to aiming at one thing while seeming to aim at another, and 
to achieving ends with the least visible effort.
All nations play the Great Game, some more than others.  The Cairhien 
country plays the Game to its highest art form.  That is not to say 
there are not players of the Game that are just as good as those found 
in Cairhien, but rather as a group the Cairhienans play the best.  Even 
the servants in Cairhien play their own version of the Game.  Andorans 
are the reluctant players, playing the Game when it is necessary.  The 
Borderlands are at the opposite end of the spectrum, considering 
themselves above the Game and maintain that they do not play.  The key 
is to appear as if one is not playing a game.  To say and do things 
with hints to other things make Daes Dae'mar an art form, but to 
misinterpret those subtleties can mean death.
     Below are listed a few of the tools used in the Great Game.  It is 
by no means an exhaustive list.  You are limited only by your 
imagination.

\c12Rumors:\c00  Rumors are an important tool in the Great Game.  The 
problem with Rumors is that they tend to have a life of their own and 
you can lose control over them.  Of course, if you are using rumors to 
undermine the integrity of others then the more out of control the 
rumor becomes the better.  However, if your goal is to spread 
misinformation you may want more control over the rumor.  One way to do 
this is to hire people to spread rumors.  There are a few rules about 
rumors you need to understand.  One being that to be effective, the 
source of the rumor should never be revealed.  In fact, it could be 
quite dangerous to you if it were found out.  Sometimes, it is better 
to have house servants such as advisors or loyal guards be the one who 
pays off others for the spreading of rumors.  One of the best ways to 
spread rumors is through the gleemen or any person who tends to travel 
a lot.  If you know the spies of others make sure the rumors are passed 
along to them as well.

\c12Bribes:\c00  Bribes are an important part of the Great Game and 
they do not have to be just in terms of money.  You can bribe with 
anything.extraordinary weapons, women - including marriage proposals 
or their hands in marriage, which is fairly easy to do if the women are 
part of your house and you are a noble, positions, wine, or various 
other favors.  It is of course important never to call these bribes, 
but rather little presents of appreciation for a job well done.  
Semantics is so very critical to a good play of the Game.

\c12Codes:\c00  Nobles are supposed to excel at writing coded messages.  
For this to work, the party you are sending the message to has to know 
how to uncode it.  Although, Jordan never states it, probably each 
house has its own code that changes as it is found out by others.  That 
code would be taught to all the house members unless a house member 
were left out due to suspicion of spying or leaking information from 
the House.  In addition, it is also likely that people who are working 
closely together would develop some way to code messages among 
themselves.  Please note, that using codes is something only nobles do 
among other nobles not servants or guards (unless the guard is also a 
noble).  You have two options.  One options is to literally develop a 
code, which is best because it takes role play to sit down and work out 
a system you can use between the parties involved.  The other options 
is to simply put at the top of the letter: this letter is written in 
code known only by other nobles of house Damodred.  And to put that 
line between astrids.  The only problem is that if any one reads it, 
while they can't claim in character knowledge, they will have OOC 
knowledge.  Codes can be a lot of fun and are used way too little.  And 
thieves should be stealing more mail than they do, cause it is often 
worth more than any gold the person might be carrying.

\c12Spies and informants:\c00  These are essential to a good play of 
the Game.  In fact, they are essential even if you supposedly don't 
play the Game.  Spies and informants are secret, they never call 
themselves that, probably not even to you.  They gather information and 
pass it on.  They can be from your House, or from other Houses, or from 
any segment of society.  Sometimes, just advertising for guards will 
get you information as you interview each potential candidate.  The 
best informant is the one that doesn't know he/she is informing.  There 
are lots of ways to get information and they don't have to be on your 
payroll.  The danger is you usually don't know the reliability of the 
information you are getting, even the person giving it to you might not 
know how reliable it is.  There is always the possibility that no 
matter how loyal your informant is to you, that they might be getting 
fed misinformation.  While not all gleeman are informants per se, it is 
always useful to have a court bard in the house for entertainment among 
other things.

\c12Aes Sedai:\c00 The Aes Sedai are useful for information and 
protection.  Aes Sedai usually have their own system of eyes and ears 
and can be helpful with the information they have.  Aes Sedai can also 
offer you protection.  Many Nobles have hired Aes Sedai to join their 
courts, though often they do not realize they are adding themselves as 
strings to the game the Amyrlin plays.  However, they can be great 
assets.  For instance, if you are fortunate enough to get a Yellow 
Ajah, then you get the bonus of having someone who can heal you as 
well, and this can come in handy.

\c12Blackmail:\c00  Blackmail, making someone pay you to not reveal 
information is quite dangerous and a highly lucrative endeavor.  This 
one is often employed in the case of channeling, and the person pays 
for your silence.  You have to make sure you don't ask for more than 
the person can pay and you must not tell anyone.  If you violate either 
of these rules then the chances are very good that the person will try 
to kill you.  To make yourself more valuable and the money they are 
paying you seem worth it to them, you can always use whatever means you 
have to offer them some level of protection.  This is not necessary but 
it can lower the likelihood they will seek to terminate you.  And don't 
limit your blackmailing to mere coinage.be creative.

\c12Kidnapping and hostage taking:\c00  Often times, it is best to have 
someone else do the actual kidnapping for you and even better if the 
kidnapped person never knows of you or sees your face.  When it comes 
time for release, be the person who tries to rescue them.  Of course, 
there are a number of variations on this theme.  If you are one of 
those evil doers and you want to put the fear of the Dark One into your 
enemies then by all means let them know . Indeed flaunt your evil 
deeds before them all, the whole nation or world.  In fact, even if you 
didn't kidnap someone take credit for it, come forward and say you have 
them.  It will increase your prestige and you may even get the money or 
other items the actual kidnapper was hoping to obtain.

See Also: DDREQS, HUNTERS, NOBILITY, HOUSES
#0
DDREQS

Life is a game. The object of the game is to stay on top of a
dangerous and ever changing world. This is done by many methods:  
bribery, cohersion, kidnapping, assassination, marriage, poisoning, and 
many other dirty tricks. The people who play this game either have 
shady ethics and ideals or do what it takes to win, caring little for 
who stands in their way. This is Daes Dae'mar, the Game of Houses.

Daes Dae'mar is a guild where you deal your hand and hope you
become the game master, not the pawn. The nobility varies greatly in 
power and status, but all hold a single goal: the wish to excel in 
politics and power. There are also the guards of the city or Houses, 
merchants, spies, even lowly stablehands, maids, and serving wenches. 
You can also dabble in the court system as a Magistrate or Thieftaker.  
If high adventure is your thing, you may even try your hand as a Hunter 
of the Horn.

All seekers must be at least LEVEL 20 and must send a background with a 
life story to DAES GL and must RP with other members of  the guild (who 
in turn MUST send an RP report to the Guildleader).  The number of 
sponsors necessary to be guilded changes with each seeker.  It depends 
on the RP and how you are rated by the guildmembers, the position you 
seek, and the House/Nation you are seeking. 

Channelers are allowed into the guild by petition and must submit a 
complete backgroud and IC training to the GL. In addition, the guild 
maintains a ratio of channelers to non-channelers.  It is very likely 
you will have to wait for an opening.  Filling of openings are NOT on a 
first come first serve bases.  The openings will be filled by the best 
Role Player among those waiting for guilding.  Playing a Channeler in 
Daes is a very delicate matter, and we wish to have people playing 
these characters to understand the IC conditions in which they play.  
Therefore we ask this extra measure be taken.

Daes Dae'mar is first and foremost a Roleplay guild, and we expect our 
players to excel in RP ability, not just code. The weapon of choice in 
Daes is subtlety and guile. Even the most lowly servant can influence 
the workings of nations. Do not let someone's station deceive you.  You 
never know who has influence upon who, or what their intentions are.

People wishing to play Nobles must post a detailed Character Background 
and have the sponsorship of the Head of the House they seek. The 
background should be very detailed and demonstrate that you have an 
understanding of the political climate of the house you are applying to 
as well as an understanding of being a noble.  The standards are quite 
high, do not be surprised if your initial background is rejected.  The
GL is always willing to work with potential seekers.  Players who have 
played a lower rank in the Daes guild tend to be the most successful 
petitioners because they have experience and understanding having 
played in the guild.

See Also:  DAES DAE'MAR, HOUSES, NOBILITY, HUNTERS
#0
DAMANE
Literally, leashed-one.
  The girls born with the ability to channel are collared by the Sul'dam.
They are like dogs, controlled by a sul'dam with an a'dam (see HELP A'DAM).
They are used as weapons, using the One Power in battles.
  Depending on the talents of the Damanes, they can be trained to find
precious minerals for the Seanchan, to make a'dams, or any other tasks that
can be executed only with the One Power.  To be touched by a Damane is a
dishonor, except for the Sul'dams.  They are feared because of their power,
but beside from that, they are seen as less than human by the Seanchan.
The Damanes are the property of the Empress.  They can not do anything
without the Sul'dam's permission.  They possess nothing.  Damanes are
possessions. Most Damanes are not allowed names.

\c01See also:\c07 Seanchan, Sul'dam, a'dam, marath'damane, Empress\c00
#0
INNS TAVERNS

   Inns and taverns are placed in various places in all the lands, where
travellers can buy food and provisions or a place to spend the night.
Traditionally used as good role-playing spots, players can stay undisturbed
in private rooms, or join as groups in the common areas to hold meetings
or celebrations. 
#0
DARKFRIEND

  Darkfriend, Friends of the Dark, the Shadowsouled, Nightrunners, they have
been called by many names by many people, but they all mean the same thing:
Someone who has forsaken the light and pledged their soul and lives to
serve the Shadow. It is not easy for many people to understand why someone
would want to become a Darkfriend, but there are many possible explanations.
One possibility is that these people are seduced by promises of \c03wealth\c00,
\c02power\c00 and even \c06immortality\c00 for their service to the Dark One.
 Others are
perhaps castoffs from society, and seek revenge against those who scorned
them, or perhaps some are forced to serve the shadow against their will,
and eventually are mired so deep that they cannot escape. Yet despite the
methods that have brought about their oaths to the dark, we can suspect that
they have served well, for the Dark One has never been a lenient master.

There is little that is truly known about those who have pledged their lives
in service to the shadow, and much that is suspected. One thing that is
known, is that a darkfriend would rather die than betray their oaths, for it
is suspected that the Lord of the Grave has found some way to punish his
minions even beyond their own death. As for where darkfriends come from,
there has been much speculation, and little hard evidence. It seems that
anyone could be one of the Friends of the Dark, regardless of what country
they are from, or their social status, from king to beggar. Those people
who have admitted to being a darkfriend before they died, have come from
all lots in life, so it seems the Lord of the Grave will use anyone he can
to advance his goals.

            \c01<Requirements to become a Darkfriend>\c00

\c05	\c00 All classes, sexes, and races are allowed in the Darkfriend guild.
\c05	 \c00You must be a minimum of level 20 to join the guild.
\c05	 \c00IC reasons why you want to become a darkfriend.
\c05	 \c00A character story and background.

            \c01<Ways to become a Darkfriend>\c00

\c02	\c00 Mail one of the Darkfriend Guildleaders(Shai'tan)
\c02	\c00 Apply for a Darkfriend book character.
\c02	 \c00Contact one of the Forsaken.
\c02	 \c00Contact somone you 'think' may be a Darkfriend.

      \c01<How your request for application will be answered>\c00

\c06	 \c00One of the Darkfriend guildleaders will mudmail you with an answer.
\c06	 \c00You will be met by a someone who will reveal themselves as a
  Darkfriend, and will ask you to accompany him/her to meet with some
  other Darkfriends who will speak to you about membership.
  (this 'interview' will be handled In Character)
\c06	\c00 One of the Forsaken will seek you out.

Other methods may be used depending on the circumstances.

\c01See also:\c07 DFPOLICY GUILDS\c00
