ENTERTAINERS

     Touching every land, reaching into the hearts and minds of royalty
and commoner alike, knowing no social boundaries, are those who are known 
as Entertainers.
     The \c09Gleefolk\c00, men and women, marked with the patch-covered cloak, 
traverse the length and breadth of the world, finding sanctuary in every 
village and inn or tavern therein. Trained to sing, make music, perform 
ballads and sonnets or poetry of the ages, or even simply entertain with
acrobats and juggling, their skill is such that they can resurrect the 
thoughts and emotions of past dead heroes. They bring a few hours of 
entertainment and joy to the lives of the citizenry, allowing them to 
forget about daily troubles and worries. However, this is not a trade for 
innocence or for such a trait to survive long. the world is a hard place, 
filled with unfriendly types that seek nothing but to bring strife and 
hardship to even these entertainers. To combat such evilness, the men and 
women who take up the Patchwork cloak are taught in the art of the dagger 
and various other unknown and dark trades to defend themselves against 
these harbingers of ill fortune. It is not known, yet suspected, that some 
of the more talented and well-established Gleefolk, dabble their fingers in 
the game that is Daes Daemar, the shadowy war of nobility that is played at 
various levels, in every land. Information is something that is useful to any 
who wish to survive, and gleefolk excel in gleaning it from almost anyone.
     The \c11Illuminators\c00 cannot be described in any other way than
 secretive,
suspicious and extremely dangerous. Their craft is deeply steeped in the 
protective cloak of mystery and misinformation,  this closely-knit and
close-mouthed group say little and reveal less whenever one tries to engage 
them in conversation. Having two chapter houses, the original in Tanchico 
and a newly established  house of secrets in Cairhien, they are a small 
group but when called upon to perform their trade, that of illuminating 
the skies with  dazzling Fireworks, there are none other who approach 
their skill or knowledge of the creation of such Fireworks. Of late, there 
seems to have been some troubles within their secretive ranks, for the 
Chapter house in Cairhien has recently burned to the ground, the leader of 
the establishment, found to be missing and presumed dead. Little is known 
that indicates the condition of the Chapterhouse in war-torn Tarabon, yet 
it is the only standing house that this mysterious group still holds. Quite
recently, a new Chapterhouse was erected outside the eastern gates of 
Caemlyn. It appears to be empty, but, who can tell what goes on past the 
thick walls that surround it.
     The \c12Menagerie\c00 are folk that travel often, from city to village,
 they 
are usually welcomed anywhere. A long train of wagons, some  filled with 
people, most filled with animals, they set up on plains and impress the
citizenry with their skills with the animals, acrobatics, balance on the
highwire, or their impressive aim. The Menagerie stays at most a month in 
any one place, moving on almost as quickly as they set up, with the wealth 
they have gleaned from those that have come to the show.

See Also: ENTREQS
#0
ENTREQS

   Greetings! The ENTERTAINERS guild is open for business and guess what, 
we want you! Yes you, to join us in the fun! There are a few requirements 
that I will list here:

     o You must be level 10 to be guilded
     o You must have a good background mailed to the Guildleader
     o You must have a good description, detailed (describing 
       how you look and what you are wearing)
     o You must gain one sponsor from the Entertainers guild
       and RP with the Guildleader
     o You must have fun!! :>

   Some people are not sure exactly what the ENTERTAINERS guild is, so I'll 
tell you a bit about us. We are composed of three factions mainly, the 
Gleemen, the Illuminators, and the Menagerie. When coming up with a 
background, keep in mind what each portion of the guild is like. The gleemen 
are singers, musicians, poets, storytellers, royal bards, yet most all are 
interested in listening for information. The Illuminators are a closed bunch, 
if you are accepted into their Chapterhouse, then your life becomes closed,
and you will have many secrets that are not to be told to outsiders. Because, 
if you do, you will be killed. Now, the Menagerie.. the GREAT Menagerie is a 
band of people who are acrobats, animal trainers, tightrope walkers, knife 
throwers and jugglers, as well as many other talented people who travel
nomadically from town to town giving shows.

See Also: ENTERTAINERS
#0
EXPERIENCE XP

Whenever you kill a monster or a player, you earn experience points.  When
enough experience points are earned, you raise a level.
Things you should know about experience points:

  * If you kill a monster of higher level than yourself, you get bonus
    experience points.  If killing a monster of lower level you'll gain
    less experience points
  * When you are grouped, you get exp calculated on the average level
    of the members in the group, divided on the total amount of members.
    Example: Three people are grouped, one level 20, one level 100 and
    a level 30. They get the exp a level (20+100+30)/3 = 50 would have
    gained, divided by three.

\c01See also: \c07GROUP, SCORE\c00
#0
FAQ "FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS" NEWBIE

   Some survival tips for you while you are new to the lands of the
Dragon's Fang; not all of them are apparent, but most of them should be
mandatory to ensure your having a good time around.

QUESTION: Where is everything?
ANSWER: Around. In this helpfile, instructions about reaching various
        places will be given starting from the recall room. You may
        always get to that room by typing "home" and pressing Enter -
        the "home" command will be working for you until you reach the
        40th level of experience.

 ---->  Type "help basic" for more about specific places.

QUESTION: Where do I find food/water?
ANSWER: Both can be found just up, north of recall near the Oval plaza.
        Just type "list" to see what is available, and "buy <item>" to
        buy something that caught your eye. For example, "buy bread" .

        To get water, just type "drink fountain" and if you have a water
        container (which you can buy from that same room if you type
        "buy skin" you can also type "fill skin fountain" and later on
        in the game "drink skin" to drink wherever you are until you
        empty it. There is a fountain in the Oval plaza.

QUESTION: How do I get in a guild?
ANSWER: You must be at least level 20 before you can join a Guild in the
        Dragon's Fang. Other than that, Role Playing your character as
        seeking your Guild of choice will draw attention to you, and you
        will be able to be guilded.
        Type "help guild" at this point for more information.

QUESTION: What are all those acronyms people use? (AFK, OOC, etc)
ANSWER: Type "help acronyms" to find what most of those mean. Ask for
        help from an immortal if you need help on something not included
        there.

QUESTION: How do I mail someone?
ANSWER: Walk to the postmaster and type "mail <person>" . End the message
        with @@ in an empty line and press enter. The postmaster is
        conveniently just Up from recall.


QUESTION: Where do I talk to lots of people at once?
ANSWER: There is a public channel called OOC which is available for
        everyone to use after reaching the 2nd level or experience. Just
        type "OOC <message>" to use it, like "OOC Hey all!" .
        Remember that since this is a public channel, you are assumed to
        use it wisely. That means, avoid spamming, and please DO not use
        four letter words to express your feelings.

QUESTION: Where do people Role Play around here?
ANSWER: Lots of places. For starters, check out the Oval Plaza (just up,
        north, west of recall), or the Golden Bowl inn (three east,
        down from the Oval plaza) .
        Or use tells/the OOC channel/the IC channel to find out where to
        find people.

QUESTION: I am low level. Where do I go to advance in levels?
ANSWER: In the first few levels, before you are powerful enough or have
        friends to help you and eq to enhance you, you are suggested to
        walk around the city you are in and use the consider command on
        mobs (monsters, guards, etc) you encounter. if you are in
        Caemlyn like most people, kill suspicious whitecloaks,
        flies, a bit later on annoying peddlers to level.
        In most cases, leveling is a matter of trial-and-error. You may
        die a few times before you understand how things work. *smile*

QUESTION: Is Player Killing allowed on the Dragon's Fang?
ANSWER: Type "help pk" .
#0
FLAGS

Players sometimes have FLAGS after their names in the WHO list.  These
flags are always in parentheses, not brackets or braces.

  FLAG        MEANING
  ----------- ---------------------------------------------------------
  (invis)     Player is invisible; you can see him/her because you are
              sensitive to the presence of invisible things.
  (writing)   Player is writing on the board; do not disturb.
  (mailing)   Player is writing mail; do not disturb.
  (deaf)      Player has chosen not to hear shouts.
  (notell)    Player has chosen not to accept tells.
  (quest)     Player is participating in a quest currently being run by
              the Gods.
  (AFK)       Player is Away From Keyboard and can't respond right now.

\c01See also:\c07 NOSHOUT, NOTELL, QUEST, STEAL, VISIBLE\c00
#0
FOOD DRINK

  Just like in Real Life(tm) you have to drink and eat, in order to keep
your stamina. On Dragons Fang, you can't die neither from thirst, nor
hunger. But, the more hungry and/or thirsty you become, the longer it'll
take you to regain mana, hitpoints and moves. And being stuck in the
Blight without food or water, and no strength to defend yourself, is
NOT a good position in life. :)
#0
FORSAKEN

The Forsaken is the name given to thirteen of the most powerful Aes
Sedai of the age of legends, thus among the most powerful ever known;
who went over to the Dark One during the War of the Shadow in return
for the promise of immortality. The Forsaken were cast into the Dark
One's prison when Lews Therin and the Hundred companions resealed the
bore, the counterstroke of this by the Dark One resulted in the male
half of the True Source becoming tainted. Among themselves, and other
darkfriends, the forsaken are known as "the Chosen" those mortals who
have been chosen by the Dark One to become one of his Immortal servants.

The names of the forsaken are:
Aginor, Asmodean, Balthamel, Be'lal, Demandred, Graendal, Ishamael,
Lanfear, Mesaana, Moghedien, Rahvin, Sammael and Semirhage.

It is believed by those with current knowledge of the events in the
world that only Demandred and Sammael remain living among the men; and
only Graendal, Mesaana, Moghedien, and Semirhage among the women
(However, it is most likely that two of the Forsaken were brought back
from the grave as Aran'gar and Osan'gar, both who wield Saidin).

A number of strange encounters, and activities suggest the possibility
either that several new Chosen have been selected by the Dark One; or
that the Lord of the Grave has in some cases reached beyond death.      

It will be noted, that due their highly developed abilities at stealth
and cunning, it is widely believed that the forsaken are still trapped in
the bore by many. Each one has spent over four hundred years honing their
channeling and manipulative abilities to a razor sharp edge. Many would  
be heros or fools seek to meet with and test themselves against any one  
of the forsaken. This has often led to the premature demise of the said  
hero or fool. At other times, when a forsaken so chooses, this person has 
been said to face a fate worse then death.

\c11Becoming one of the Forsaken:\c00

ALL Forsaken are book characters and need to be interview by the DF/FS GLs.

To apply for one of the forsaken book characters, you must Mudmail Shai'tan,
or Shaidar with a formal application for the character you are interested in.
Please include the following information in the application:


1) The name of the Forsaken book character you are interested in.
2) Which of the Wheel of Time books you have read.
3) Why you are interested in this character.
4) What other characters you have played on Dragon's Fang, including other
   book characters.
5) Any guilds you have belonged to on Dragon's Fang.
6) How often you will be able to play the character.
7) What you know, book wise about the Forsaken you are applying for.
8) Any other information you wish me to know.

Sometime after Shai'tan or Shaidar receives your application, you will be
contacted either by Mud mail, or personally if Shai'tan or Shaidar are on
at the time. You will be informed if your application has been accepted,
or refused, and why. If you are accepted, you will be interviewed by
Shai'tan, who will ask you between 15 to 35 questions to determine your
book knowledge. If you pass this test, you will be given the character
you have applied for.

(Note from Shai'tan)
  To all those who wish to play one of the dreaded forsaken, there are two
pieces of information you should know. One, you can apply for one of the
forsaken book characters that is already taken, and if I think you will
perform better than the existing person, you will replace him/her. Second,
if you join the forsaken guild you CAN NOT have any other darkfriend 
characters on Dragon's Fang. This rule exists so that the forsaken will 
be an active part of the mud; and there will be no exception to this 
rule, ever.
#0
FSPOLICY
The Chosen, as roleplayers, should be of the highest quality and well versed 
in current mud Policy and guidelines. Due to their unequalled power relative 
to mortal players and In Character nature they are also highly influencial 
to all roleplay on Dragons Fang. It for this reason that players of Chosen, 
like all Darkfriends, are so only because of the approval of the Darkfriend 
Guildleaders and if such a situation or circumstance shall arise where a 
Darkfriend Guildleader decides that they should be removed then it is so 
without question or appeal. All Chosen players must seek to improve and 
expand the roleplay of the Darkfriends and the mud as a whole and, in all 
instances, roleplay true to their characters history, book definied 
abilities and status, and within the guildelines set down for them.

Equipment:
In the Chosen guild room an unlimited supply of Chosen guild equipment will, 
and is, stored. Each Chosen may take, and use, as much as they feel 
necessary. It is advised that each Chosen have at least two full sets of 
tooled equipment for their disguises. The Chosen guild equipment shall 
never, under any circumstances, be given, borrowed or used by anyone not of 
the Chosen Guild. It is also required when tooling the Chosen equipment that 
forsaken remain a keyword for administrative purposes.

Promotion/Demotion:
Chosen are often the primary instigators for the promotion and demotion of 
Darkfriends. Each Chosen may recommend, at any time, to the Darkfriend 
Guildleaders for the promotion or demotion of Darkfriends based on In 
Character circumstances. Chosen may also recommend promotion and/or award of 
Questpoints based on the witness of excellent roleplay and effort.

Skills:
Each Chosen is given, in code, all weaves and skills that the Darkfriend 
Guildleaders can be satisfied is In Character or reflective of their In 
Character status and relative abilities. It is advised not to discuss with 
anyone besides other members of the Chosen Guild that skills and attributes 
a character has.

Teaching:
A Chosen may roleplay teach any skill or weave In Characterly appropriate to 
both student and teacher if the skill or weave in question is gainable by 
mortal players at the Trainer or is considered  roleplay gainable or 
instructable on the MUD. The Chosen may also teach, when appropriate the 
Darkfriend Guild skills the student is In Characterly and Out of Characterly 
entitled. However, without the express permission of a Darkfriend 
Guildleader no Chosen may teach any Chosen guild skills or weaves and skill 
such as balefire, compulsion, inversion, forcible turning or any other 
unbalancing ability.

Killing:
As per the general MUD guildelines a Chosen must in all instances roleplay 
their characters reflective of their abilities and nature and be true to 
their In Character history. As such if In Characterly a Chosen finds it 
necessary to attempt to maim, hurt or kill another player based on the 
roleplay that unfolds then a Chosen should and must roleplay the response 
the situation requires. In all cases roleplay is preferred to code when 
dealing with another Darkfriend. A Chosen should be of sufficient skill as a 
roleplayer that code is generally not used at all.

Shadowspawn:
No Chosen shall roleplay the creation of mortal shadowspawn players without 
the approval of the Darkfriend Guildleaders. Chosen shall also seek approval 
before emote or echoing the use of rare or restricted forms of Shadowspawn 
such as Gholam.

Naeblis:
The position of Naeblis is given or taken away with due consideration of In 
Character circumstance and activity. All loyal soldiers of the Shadow 
should, as in all instances, give as much authority to the Naeblis as he or 
she can enforce. Naeblis is the strongest and most cunning and ruthless of 
the Great Lords servants.

Disguises:
Disguise, being a Chosen guildskill, is a powerful ability that is 
restricted to its ranks. The following guidelines apply;
Darking - a Chosen may ask a Darkfriend Guildleader or any approved Immortal 
to code dark (guild) their disguise to ensure the integrity of their hidden 
identity.
Guilds - before disguising into a guild besides the Darkfriend and Chosen 
guilds a Chosen player must seek the permission of the Guildleader in 
charge. For long term or significant roleplay the general approval of the 
guildleader should be sought but notification of all intentions is not 
required.
Names - disguised names should be, of course, appropriate to the Wheel of 
Time theme of the MUD and shall not be of a player past or present without 
due In Character circumstance and notification.

Revealing Darkfriends:
Inline with MUD policy and in suppliment, under no circumstances without the 
specific approval of a Darkfriend Guildleader or the player in question, 
shall any person reveal Out of Characterly reveal the name and associations 
of a guilded Darkfriend. For a Chosen, to do so is to resign as well as 
suffer the consequences of this action.

Out of Character Interactions:
The Chosen are Book Characters and in suppliment to MUD policy they may not 
interact with players in any Out of Character fashion that is not conductive 
to current or future roleplay. This includes assisting mortals to level or 
equip and protect themselves.

Death:
Chosen, like any players on the MUD, have a duty to roleplay themselves with 
the integrity and abiltities of their character in mind. If as a consequence 
of In Character actions a Chosen is killed, then unless otherwise stated  
and arranged by the Darkfriend Guildleader the following proceedure applies-
The Chosen shall return to the room in which the incident occurred and sleep 
there for a 30 minute timeout period. After such a time they will be 
unaffected of any and all injuries and then be considered rewoven into the 
Pattern by the Lord of the Grave. While the 30 minute interval takes place 
the Chosen in question may not take any In Character action.

Continued in FSPOLICY2...
#0
FSPOLICY2
...Continued from FSPOLICY

Mindtraps:
Mindtraps, as In Characterly shown, may only be introduced and enforced on a 
player with the approval of the Darkfriend Guildleaders. It is a rare and 
significant event and, as such, the wishes of the player concerned shall be 
considered.

Angreal, Saangreal and Terangreal (*angreal)
A Chosen shall not give any type of *angreal to a player In Characterly, or 
in code, without the permission of one of the Darkfriend Guildleaders in 
suppliment to MUD policy. In the case of adam and other binding collars, 
with Chosen/Darkfriend links the normal Roleplay guidelines apply but in 
Chosen/Chosen roleplay the guidance of the Darkfriend Guildleaders should be 
sought but is not required.

Forced Turnings:
Under no circumstances may a player who is Out of Characterly unwilling be 
forced to In Characterly join the Darkfriend Guild. Before any such roleplay 
proceeds approval must be gained from both the player as well as one of the 
Darkfriend Guildleaders. The player must also be informed of the In 
Character consequences of being forcibly turned against their will which 
result from the means.

Darking (guilding):
A Chosen may ask either Darkfriend Guildleader to guild a mortal player into 
the Darkfriend Guild when he or she is In Characterly satisfied they shall 
serve as such. Most guilding is solely based on the recommendation of the 
Chosen and care should be taken to ensure that the player is both In and Out 
of Characterly ready to join. This means making sure their level of 
roleplay, character history, description etc are acceptable. If a Chosen 
does not want to specifically sponser a seeker however but still wishes to 
roleplay or recommend aspects of a player to the Darkfriend Guildleaders 
then they are encouraged to do so.

Bonds:
The Chosen-Minion bond is, unless otherwise stated, an Out of Character 
relationship between a Chosen and his or her minion. It is a symbolic and 
representative of the In Character roleplay they have engaged in. Chosen may 
only bond Darkfriends of rank higher or equal to the Basic Member Rank. Due 
to the nature only the highest and most trusted and loyal servants are to be 
bonded.
Chosen may of course, after having grounding themselves with the knowledge, 
bond a minion or other using an Aes Sedai or Ashaman type bond. This 
however has the same ramifications as any who weave it and shall endure the 
conseuqneces of such. Under no circumstances shall a Chosen Out of 
Characterly bond anyone nor shall they bond a non-guilded Darkfriend. In 
place of an actual woven bond it is best advised to use the same basic 
method but modified as circumstances permit, that Moiraine Aes Sedai used in 
the Eye of the World when she warded coins and gave them to her charges.

In Addition:
The above guidelines and policy are enforcible by the Darkfriend 
Guildleaders and the failure of any Chosen to comply may result in their 
immediate removal, and, in the case of code abuse, the deletion of any other 
players involved. The Darkfriend Guildleaders, being merciful and just gods, 
can and will consider surrounding circumstance and reason before making a 
decision and may give specific permission where appropriate and required for 
the guidelines to be altered or alternativly interpreted. In all 
circumstances common sense should be used and the wishes of all parties 
concerned weighed with due consideration.
#0
GOOOC GOIC
\c02   The OOC and IC states of a character on Dragon's Fang is easily
determined with simple code; this will affect everything you do in
different ways - here is how it works.\c00
   Any given character can either be \c01IC\c00 or \c01OOC\c00 at any given
time. Type:

\c01GOIC\c00 to switch to In Character mode. Now, you will be In Character
where you are on the MUD (you cannot claim to be Out of Character if someone
wishes to Roleplay with you in the room you are in). All your channeling is
considered to be IC - and if you overchannel, you burn out. Your taint, if
you are a male channeler, may increase with various results.
   You can always switch to In Character mode simply by typing this command;
nothing can prevent you from Roleplaying whenever you feel like it.
\c01GOOOC\c00 to switch to Out of Character mode. Now, you will be considered
to be Out of Character wherever you are. You may still burn out, and, of
course, channeling is still IC. On the other hand, you cannot see what
In Character people are saying or doing while in this mode.
   In order to be able to switch to Out of Character mode, you mustn't have
Roleplayer anything for a small while - that is, not have used the "emote"
and "say" commands for a small time period.
#0
GUILD GUILDS

  The Guild area is the place where mortals may go to escape the troubles
and perils of a cruel world.  Each guild is heavily guarded, so that only
members may enter the building.  Guilds are also the places where people
come to learn and practice the skills of their trade.

The guilds that you can join are the following:

\c06	\c07Aiel:\c00
          The descendants of the people who worked as servants before
          the Breaking, they are considered to be the fiercest warriors
          living, as a group regarded. The live in the Three-Fold Land
          and refer to all other peoples as 'Wetlanders'

\c06	\c07Asha'man:\c07
          Male channelers who have joined a society to aid the Dragon
          Reborn at Tarmon Gaidon, the Last Battle. They are considered
          to be the elite forces following the Dragon Reborn as they can
          wield Saidin, but the price is high; they will all eventually
          go mad because of the Taint on Saidin placed there by the Dark One.

\c06	\c07Band of the Red Hand:\c00
          A rather haphazard group of people all following
          Mat Cauthon, a Ta'veren with incredible luck and one of the child-
          hood friends of Rand al'Thor. This 'army' has so far never lost.

\c06	\c07Children of the Light:\c07
          A group of zealous, some say fanatic, soldiers
          in a rigid army regarding themselves to be the only true followers
          of the Light. They have been accused of many transgressions, but
          never so that others can hear; they are numerous and very skilled
          fighters.

\c06      \c07Daes Dae'mar:\c00
          A guild that spans across the entire Nation and consists of
          Nobles, guards, Magistrates, Thieftakers, servants, and more,
          all willing or forced players of the Gr. These people
          will lie, poison, act diplomatic, or even assassinate to get
          what they want: bettering themselves and their rank or House.

\c06	\c07Darkfriend:\c00
          People who for different reasons have turned to the Shadow
          and now follow the Lord of the Dark. This is the only guild that
          people can join together with another guild.

\c06    \c07Entertainers:\c00
          Rogues of the lands, bearers of tales and myths. They make a man
          a legend or leave him as nothing more than a speck of dirt on the
          ground. Entertainers come in many forms: Gleeman with rich stories
          or saucy bartunes, Illuminators and their mystical fireworks,
          actors of the stage, trainers and performers of traveling
          menageries. These men and women travel often and try to evade
          being tied down by anything.
        
\c06	\c07Forsaken:\c00
          They call themselves the Chosen are -very- few, a dozen or
          so. They are those who have been selected by the Dark One to
          be immortals as reward for a long service, spanning over millenia
          in most instances. They are invariably superb channelers and
          fighters, better than almost all mortals, and most people regard
          them as myths or sagas. ALL Chosen are book characters and need
          to apply by interview.

\c06      \c07Hunters of the Horn:
          Those who have taken the Oath at the Square of Tammuz in Illian
          and now dedicate their time in search of the legendary Horn
          of Valere. Many of these Hunters become legends themselves;
          Gleeman sing praises even to those long gone. It is said that
          whoever finds the Horn of Valere will become a true legend.
	  (Note: this is a part of the Daes Dae'mar guild)

\c06      \c07Kin:\c00
	  The channeling Healers of the mud, these women form a circle
          of mostly runaways from the White Tower: girls who did not make
	  it as Aes Sedai or were too scared to stay. Instead they use their
	  channeling ability in Ebou Dar to help heal the injured and
   	  act as mediators, like any strong woman would. The Kin know quite
	  a bit about herbs and medicine, and though they are not considered
	  as strong as Aes Sedai, they have their tricks, and also take most
	  any girl who shows she can channel, as their training is less rigorous.

\c06	\c07Ogier:\c00
          A race of very large, very kind and very slow people, who are
          spoken of as the Builders, due to their superb skills in building
          cities and pieces of art. They live in Steddings and live a very
          long life, more than three centuries generally. Lately the have
          become shy and secluded and keep to their Steddings.

\c06	\c07Rebel Aes Sedai:\c00
          Aes Sedai who have broken with the Tower and now are
          placed in Salidar. They are ruled by Egwene al'Vere, a childhood
          friend of Rand al'Thor.

\c06	\c07Rebel Warders:\c00
          Warders who follow their Sedai who have broken with the Tower.

\c06	\c07Seanchan:\c00
          People coming back across the Aryth Ocean to reclaim what
          they think of as theirs: the rest of the world. They are the
          descendants of Artur Hawkwing, one of the greatest rulers that
          ever has lived.

\c06    \c07Tuatha'an:\c00
          People who follow The Way of the Leaf, a way of nonviolence and
          happiness, commonly called Tinkers. Most people, especially in
          large cities, view the Tinkers with fear, as they are reputated
          (without much evidence) to steal and subvert youths. Tinkers
          spend their lives traveling from place to place in colored wagons


\c06	\c07Tower Aes Sedai:\c00
          Aes Sedai who chose to stay with the Tower when it split,
          and who still are governed by Elaida, the Amyrlin Seat in Tar Valon.
          The Tower Aes Sedai have little but contempt for those who became
          rebels, but are still trying to make them come back.

\c06	\c07Tower Warders:\c00
          The Warders to the Sedai that chose to stay in the Tower
          when it split. They are also called the Younglings.

You need to be \c03level 20\c00 before you can join any Guild on the Dragon's
Fang, except for the Tuatha'an, who are not allowed to level.

   After you reach the 20th level of experience (thus proving you know at
least some basic things about the Mud, and that you have a certain degree
of dedication - enough to level that far) you may Role Play and seek the
Guild of your choice.

Remember to seek your Guild in an \c02IC\c00 way - that is, seek the one most
appropriate to the way you want to play your character, not according to
the bonuses you will get in skills or the power of its equipment.
   For most Guilds around, there are specific help files. You can try
typing "\c03help <Guild name>\c00" for details, or ask on the OOC channel about
it. Alternatively, you may contact that Guild's own Guild Leaders (the
Immortals responsible for it) to ask anything you may need.

         \c01See also info on each guild for more information.\c00
