#0
theme
  Dragon's Fang is a roleplaying MUD, set in the world of Robert Jordan's
wonderful bookseries "The Wheel of Time". We still do allow hack'n'slash
though, but we wish it mostly to be a complement to RP, not a substitute.
Becuse of our direction towards the WoT-series, we want people to choose
names that fit into the WoT-realms.

  This means, no characters named Tjoflojt, Killer, MasterBlaster, Terminator
SlaskTratt or similar. Also, even if the name might fit, don't choose to
wellknown names from other bookseries. For instance, Gandalf, Sauron, Saruman
Raistlin etc might be good names, they're too wellknown to be really good
names.

But, the main question remains, what the bl**dy `ell is roleplaying?

 A hard question to answer, since propably all people invovled in
roleplaying has different definitions. But roughly, you could say
that you make a character, give him a name, and try to think out a
so called 'background-story' for your character. Both name and story
should fit into the WoT-world. Now you log onto the game with your
character, and try to play him accordingly to how you figured your
character should behave in different situations. (Almost like acting).
So, all you have to do now, is to play your character, along with
other ppl from all the corners of the world, and try to have a really
good time. Only one thing is required: \c07creativity!\c00

One important hint though:

Do not use 'impossible' knowledge in your RP. For instance, if you see a
character in the city named Demandred, this is so called OOC-information.
You might now this player is a Forsaken, but your character won`t!

And perhaps the most important at all. Every player you meet on DF, will be
here to have fun, to RP in the WoT-world. So you should live by the golden
rule. Don't do anything towards others, you don't want others to do to you.

\c01See also:\c07 WOT, RPHELP or RPCHARACTER, WOTRESOURCES\c00
#0
rpexp
Roleplaying Experience
   
   Every character on Dragon's Fang can gain levels and increase their
power by leveling; this is usually done by killing mobs and being
awarded for it, but now there is another way to achieve that:
   When you Role Play in a room with someone else, you will start
receiving Experience Points for it - more as you continue, encouraging
long sessions over short ones. You and your partner(s) have to be IC at 
the time, and some following of good Rp etiquette will even grant you
better results - for example, if you have a doing for yourself.
#0
rwarders rebel-warders
  The Rebel Warders are a group of elite warriors that fled the
White Tower in Tar Valon, center of Aes Sedai power, due to
circumstances, they felt were unjust and unlawful. The stilling
and rumored execution of Siuan Sanche, sent some of the Aes Sedai
in the White Tower, fleeing from the shining walls and as
faithful protectors of these powerful women, the Warders
accompanied their sworn charges in their flight. 
  Finding themselves in Salidar, the now Rebel Aes Sedai began to
consolidate their power, gathering more strength for their
eventual strike back at the White Tower and the perpetrator who
began the troubles between Aes Sedai, the false Amyrlin Seat,
Elaida. 
  The Warders have kept their skills well honed, continually
sweeping the forests around their Altaran strong hold, preventing
knowledge of their temporary seat of power, from spreading to Tar
Valon. 
  To assist in the retaking of the White Tower, this Rebel
organization has formed two other military machines, separate
from the elite Warders. The Rebel Watch and the Rebel Army, the
former led by the Blademaster and Warder Khorne, the latter by
former Captain General Gareth Bryne of the Queen's Armies in
Andor. These two new military forces will assist in the
dethroning of Elaida and the installation of who they feel, to
be the true Amyrlin Seat, Egwene. 

  To join the Rebel Warders, Watch, or Army,  you must fulfil the
following.

- Must not be capable of channeling.
- Must have a background mailed to Bailford and Alessio.
- Must be at least level 20.
- Must have a strong desire to roleplay.
- Must have five sponsors, two of which must be full Warders.

\c01See also:\c07 RWARDER_EQ, RWARDER_RANKS\c00
#0
BLADEMASTER
  A title first bestowed in the Age of Legends for valiant
service and extreme skill with the blade, this very elite group
of swordsmen were given a blade rot of the Power,
causing it to be unbreakable, no matter the length of time or the
amount of use. These blades were bestowed with the mark of the
Heron, a stylized image of a bird that was etched into the steel
of the weapon. So marked, these unmatched masters of the blade,
survived the various wars that have marked the history of this
world and have descended into a group of about a hundred
swordsmen in current times. 
  Although the blades wielded by the contemporary masters have
lost their power-forged aspect, due to the Aes Sedai's inability
to make such weapons in present times, they do well with replicas
of the ancient weapons, the heron still a mark of their skill.
  To become a Blademaster, one must seek out a master and
convince him to teach you the advanced skill of their most elite
art. This training takes the form of years, sometimes more than
a decade, before the student succeeds or fails to gain
the heron. Another method is to challenge a Blademaster and take
his mark by defeating him in single, fair combat. This is rarely
done though it has occurred in the recent past and at various
points down through the ages. 
  On Dragon's Fang, we have modified the Blademaster seeking
system slightly, though we have tried to keep it as close to the
books as possible. Any wishing to become a Blademaster, must mail
Khenten and myself, (Cassin) applications which state your wish
to do so. You must include in this application the amount of time
you have played on the mud, whether you have skill or previous
training in emote fighting, how active you will be on the mud,
and various other bits that you think would set you above the
other applicants. Next, you must mail a background to the two 
of us, a background that must be fleshed out and well planned, we
want the best of the best to receive the Blademaster honor. This
does not mean you must be a Lan-type character, all steely
determination and unshakable confidence and strength. It means
you must be realistic, creative, reasonable and logical about
your background. 
  The Blademaster seekers will be narrowed down slightly to an
undetermined number, most likely three, though there may be more
who qualify to seek the Blademaster status. The seekers will be
given a certain length of time to complete their training with a
Blademaster and if they have not done so to the satisfaction of
the Blademaster or myself and Khenten, they will fail to become
one of the honored few. At this time, the process of Blademaster
seeking will be reopened for new seekers.  
  After the selection process has been completed, the seekers
will be taken to a Tourney, an event that will occur every
handful of months and that will be open to the mud to join and
enjoy. Anyone interested in fighting in such a Tourney, more
information will be available through prompting Cassin or Khenten
as to dates, times etc.
The Blademaster seekers will be observed and judged for their
emote fighting skill. When the Tourney is completed, the seekers,
if they are deemed good enough, will be able to follow rp along
until they come in contact with a Blademaster and will be
authorized to train under said Blademaster, pending the approval
of said Blademaster. The process will be explained further to
the seekers once they have reached the training stage so I will
not go into depth about it here but if there are any questions
concerning any aspect of this new system, please ask and your
inquiries will be answered swiftly.

SEE ALSO: TOURNEY
#0
BLADEMASTER_JUDGING "BLADEMASTER JUDGING"

Blademaster Judging System

There are four different ways to score in the tournament.

1) Your Background: this is submitted when you apply to be
   involved in the Blademaster tourney. It should consist of any
   training or conflict rp you have participated in and should also
   include some non-roleplayed history of your character. 

2) Elegance of Style: This category is taken into consideration
   when you are sparring an opponent. The Judge will take into
   consideration the grace of your motions, as well as the eloquence
   and verbosity of your emotes. This category has a maximum score
   of ten points.

3) Realism: this category is judged upon during your spar and
   consists of the logistics of your maneuvers both in offence and
   defence, the understanding of momentum and the physics of your
   maneuvers, taking into account the stature of your opponent and
   to spar accordingly in terms of physicality and finally the lack
   of a superhuman syndrome, to take hits when appropriate. This
   category is also given a ten point scoring.

4) Judge's discretion: This category, judged upon during the
   spar, is completely up to the judge's themselves. It takes into
   account all the miscellaneous factors in an emote spar, how much
   ooc clarification is necessary and asked for, ooc attitude,
   entertainment value and interest of the spar. This category is
   given a scoring of ten points.

The judging system in itself, is fairly simplistic. First, your
background is analyzed and given a score out of ten, which d
determines whether you are able to enter the tourney. The basic
score on your background required to participate is five points
of ten.

The other three categories are scored by the three judges from
the Blademaster council and are decided upon by either the judge
watching the spar or reading the logs of the spar. Each judge
gives a score out of ten for each category. The score for an
individual category is averaged out to give you a score of ten in
each category and therefore a maximum of 30 in the entire spar.
When you have completed your first spar in the first weekend,
you will have a score from your first spar, out of 30. When you
spar again, the same system as outlined above, will apply
exactly, giving you another score out of 30. The scores of your
first and second spars will be averaged together to give you a
score out of 30 points gained via sparring. When the background
is included at this point, you will have a maximum of 40 points.
The total scores will be announced at this point and the top six
participants, with the highest scoring, will be moved into the
final round, to be held a week exactly after the first day of the
first round. 

Your spar in the final round will  be judged exactly as the
first round was, therefore, another score of a maximum of 30 will
be announced and averaged into the scores from your first two
spars. The entire total for a single participant for the tourney
will be a maximum of 40 points, 10 for the background and three
spars of 30 which will all be averaged together to come up with a
score of 30 and then 40 when the background is added.

SEE ALSO: BLADEMASTER_POLICY, BLADEMASTER_TOURNEY
#0
BLADEMASTER_TOURNEY "BLADEMASTER TOURNEY"

Blademaster tournament and structure

The structure of the Blademaster tourney is as follows.

- Once accepted into the Tournament, you will be required to
  spar twice in the initial round that will begin on a thursday and
  end on a Sunday, three days later. All 16 accepted participants
  will be matched up against one another to spar, a log of which
  will be sent, unedited, into  dfblademasters@egroups.com to be
  reviewed by the three judges. If you cannot log the spar,, ask
  your opponent to do so. Failing that, you may ask one of the
  Blademaster council members to invigilate the spar and to submit
  the log of the combat to the Egroups.

- After you have completed your first spar, your log will be
  analyzed and scored by the three judges and you will be given the
  appropriate score as has been laid out in the help Blademaster_
  judging file. No matter how you score, be it excellently or
  poorly, you will be given the opportunity to spar once again
  during that weekend and the same procedure concerning the logs
  stated above, will be followed.

- The score of the two spars that you participate in, will be
  averaged together to give you a maximum score of 30. The Six
  highest scoring participants of the Tourney will then advance to
  the second and final round, to be held on the thursday after the
  tourney began, exactly one week later.

- The six finalists will spar for a third and final time that
  weekend, the same logging procedure and scoring system applying
  as well. Once the three spars have been scored, the top three
  score holders, will be awarded Herons with honorable mention
  given to the other three finalists.

- Final note: If your assigned spar partner, for some reason,
  does not show up during the four days in the first or second
  round, you do not wait and get disqualified for their  inability
  to make the tourney. Merely ask one of the Bm council members,
  not currently judging the tourney, to spar you and you will be
  given a score based upon that spar.

SEE ALSO: BLADEMASTER_POLICY, BLADEMASTER_JUDGING
#0
BLADEMASTER_POLICY "BLADEMASTER_POLICY"

Anyone seeking the Heron, as well as current Blademasters
should read the following.

1) If wishing to enter a Tourney Email your background, both
   character history and rped history, to
   dfblademasters@egroups.com. It is suggested but not required,
   that you submit a spar along with the background  as a small
   example of your emote fighting abilities.

2) There will never be more than ten Blademasters on the game.
   They are held to an activity level thus if they do go inactive,
   spots will open but ten is the maximum.

3) There will be no more than five Blademasters per guild and a
   maximum of eight Warders is built into this cap, to allow for
   diversity in the Heron.

4) No blademaster may have more than one prodigy. Thus, if you
   are asking a current Blademaster to prodigy you and he or she
   already has one, it  won't be allowed and you will be forced to
   seek the heron either through prodigying yourself to another Bm
   or by entering a tourney.

5) You may not have more than one Blademaster character. This
   rule does not apply to Blademaster book characters.

6) You may have a Blademaster and a Prodigy or a blademaster and
   a Respected but not all three nor two of any save Respected.

7) Channeler blademasters are strongly discouraged. While
   channelers may, if  their backgrounds are reasonable, participate
   in the tournament, they will be strongly  handicapped score-wise
   in an attempt to attain a heron-marked blade. This policy does
   not affect  the Respected ranking.

8) Randland's swordmasters are a male-dominated group ICly. In
   acknowledging this, like channelers, while females are welcome
   to participate in the tournament if their  backgrounds and
   training are reasonable, they will be strongly handicapped
   score-wise in  an attempt to attain a heron-marked blade. This
   be played by a non book character blademaster, the only
   circumstance under which someone may  have two characters with
   the heron marked blade. A book character blademaster gets the 
   sword, and the pretitle. They may not take on a prodigy, or
   otherwise sponsor  blademastery seekers or teach blademastery
   skills. In the event of the death of a book character in  any way
   for any reason, the heron marked sword must be taken out of play,
   either by being  returned to the guild armory, if appropriate,
   being lost to shadowspawn, or otherwise being  destroyed. Book
   Character players will not be offered the blademaster title on
   another alt in the event of the book character's death. Forsaken
   will be set to the rank "Unknown", the only Forsaken blademaster 
   currently alive is Sammael. Book characters, such as Galad and
   Gawyn, who should have the Respected or  Prodigy rankings ICly,
   will receive it. 

10) A Veteran blademaster may not take on a prodigy, or otherwise
    sponsor blademastery seekers or teach blademastery skills. In
    the event of the death of a Veteran  blademaster, the heron
    marked sword must be taken out of play, either by being returned
    to the  guild armory, if appropriate, being lost to shadowspawn,
    or otherwise being destroyed.  Veteran players will not be
    offered the blademaster title on another alt in the event of 
    their death. Moving veterans from "Veteran" to "Blademaster" or
    Unknown status will be handled  on a case by case basis by the
    committee, likely based on the activity of the veteran,  the
    status of the caps when the request is made, why they went
    inactive in the first place,  and possibly the submission of some
    spars.

11) The Death of Blademasters:  Please see the "Book Character"
    and "Veteran" sections regarding the death  of people with these
    ranks. Respected always have the option of transferring their
    title to another  character provided that the IC requirements for
    Respected are met. Blademaster and Unknown ranked individuals
    when killed by NPCs or in any  fashion other than a fair
    sword-to-sword combat, will be permitted to choose another alt, 
    including the rename, to receive their blademaster status,
    subject to background approval of the  committee, and the caps.
    If the blademaster does not wish another blademaster alt, their 
    spot remains open for the next tournament. The sword of the
    character who dies must be  taken out of play, either by being
    returned to the guild armory, if appropriate, being lost to 
    shadowspawn, or otherwise being destroyed. If a Blademaster or
    Unknown ranked individual is killed by fair  sword-to-sword
    combat, a log of the combat must be sent to the committee, along
    with the background and  IC training of the killer. The committee
    will then convene to determine the disposition of  the heron
    marked sword. Until a ruling is made the sword is to be
    considered out of play.  Either the killer will be granted the
    heron marked sword, or the combat will be treated the  same as
    any other blademaster death as described in the previous
    paragraph. This method of  attaining the heron marked sword is
    discouraged, and far from guaranteed. 

12) Powerforged blades: First, while they may be decorated
    differently, all powerforged blades are  identical in shape and
    size. Second, allocations on powerforged blades will remain the
    same for all  current blademasters. The awarding of power-wraught
    blades to future blademasters will be based on  whether the
    blademaster wants one, IC factors, and some random factor to be
    determined by the council. Codewise the only difference between
    powerforged and normal heron-marked  blades (with the exception
    of Lan's and Rand's which are treated differently for a variety
    of reasons), is that, to reflect the slightly better balance of
    a powerforged blade, they  have a slightly better average damage.
    The maximum damage and all other affects are the  same. 

See also: BLADEMASTER_JUDGING, BLADEMASTER_TOURNEY
