RWARDER_EQ
Cloak, *Sword, Ring, Scabbard, *(2) Medal

*1- Dependant on Rank
*2- Special Rp eq given to only the most devoted Warders


at Master of Trainees, Instructor and Gaidin:
    Cloak, Scabbard, Bracelet, Heron Bracelet, Sword
at Warder: Cloak, Scabbard, Bracelet, Sword
at Tested: Scabbard, Bracelet, Sword
at Trainee: Bracelet, Sword
at Student: Bracelet, Sword

See also: RWARDER and RWARDER_RANKS
#0
RWARDER_RANKS

Student
----------------------
When a man, or boy joins the Tower in hopes of becoming a Warder,
he must first become a Student. In this short period of time he
must show his knowledge in the blade and in other things that would
be desired from a Sedai. Once a Student makes the oath to become
a Trainee, he can never turn back.

Trainee
----------------------
When a man goes through the student stage and passes, he becomes a
trainee. This starts his life in the ways of the Warder. Trainee is the
harshest time for a Warder, and since the Tower has been Broken
moer Warders are needed. If a Trainee passes his Training he becomes
part of the Tower Guard.

Tested
-------------------------
A Trainee who in terms in no longer a Trainee. He has proven himself to
his Instuctors and has stabilized his standing within the Guild. He
has gained the Cloak, but not been Bonded. This Rank is either a Life
Long rank or a waiting period to becoming bonded.


Warder
----------------------------
A Warder is a Trainee who has finally gained the Cloak, and has become
Bonded.
Some warders have gone straight from Trainee to Bonded, but most
Warders were part of the Tower Guard at some point. This is the most common
rank in the Guild.

Instructor
-----------------------------
An Instructor is a Warder, who knows the forms and the ways of battle.
He also knows the ways of tracking and in short the most effiecient
ways to protect and keep the Sedai safe. They are the best Warders,
and teach the other on how to improve themselves.

Gaidin
-----------------------------
Gaidin is a basic honor Rank. These are Instructors who either
have been promoted through constant ability, or that Warder who would
be an Instructor but is constantly out in the World with his Sedai.
A Gaidin is supposed to be the same Ranking as an Instructor but it
has been known that some Gaidin have even respect from a
Master of Trainees.

Master of Trainees
-----------------------------
There can only be 1 to 3 Master of Trainees at once. These Warders
are Instructors who are the recruiters, and the Trainers of the Students and
Trainees. Only The highest devoted and respected Warder ever attains
such a Rank.
#0
SEANCHAN SEANDAR

        The Empire of the Seanchan has a long and detailed history.
Descendants from the Empire of Hawking, these people crossed the Arynth
sea long ago to settle the land of Seandar. Subduing the warring
people of the continent, the people under Luthair Paendrag brought
order and peace to the land.
        Such a victory was not without a price. The Aes Sedai of the
area had caused so much strife and conflict that the Seanchan felt
necessary to make sure that no such problem would plague their Empire.
The a'dam was created, and a legacy was born. Taming the Aes Sedai
along with the fantastical beasts brought in from other worlds during
the Age of Legends, the Seanchan conquered the entire continent and
beat back the Blight.
        After a time, a complex cast system began to evolve, taken directly
from the culture of the conquerers, and from the beaten people. Slavery
was never completely stomped out by Hawking's people, and began to make
its way into their culture. A rigid hierarchy formed, with those directly
related to the Blood of Hawking as rulers of the Empire. The beaten
people took lower cast positions as slaves, and the lower classes.
        As time went on, lines became blurred. Some slaves rose to
great power in the ruling houses. They were known as so'jhin, a slave
who ran a house in the name of their Lord. Members of the Blood changed
as well, people were awarded the titles of nobility for acts they
committed in the name of the Empire.
        With their Empire solidified, the Empress of the Seanchan began
to make plans for the return of her people to the land of Hawking. Much
to her suprise, the people of Hawkings land had not kept their promises
to him and kept his empire together. They had degenerated and fought
amongst themselves for power. Outraged, the Seanchan swore to bring
these Oathbreakers back into line and re-establish the glory and splendor
of the Empire that Hawking built.
        The Seanchan of this mud are currently in hiding, spying on the
Oathbreakers after the failed assault of the Seanchan forces at Falme.
They wish to collect data about the Oathbreakers to better help them
in their war, and to strike out when possible to capture rouge Aes Sedai
to leash them and make them damane.

See Also: SEANRANKS, SEANREQS, SEANCULTURE, SEANRP
#0
SEANCULTURE

        The Seanchan culture is completely different than any other
unique culture in the Wheel of Tyme series. It has a very different
feel than that of say the Aiel, or of Shara.  Some things that set them
apart, and used to differentiate them, are their bug-shaped armor and the
soft slur their speech has from being used to speaking both common
language and the Old Tongue.
        In many ways, the Seanchan are obsessed with honor. Honor
in their station, honor to their Empire, honor on even how their hair
is cut and their nails are painted. An easy example to relate them
to in real life would be that of the Japanese.
        Eye contact is very important to the Seanchan. Those who are of
a lower station should not make direct eye contact with those of a higher
station. To be allowed such is a great honor. This rules applies all
the way up in the Seanchan infrastructure to the Empress, who no one is
allowed to look directly at her face without permission.
        Bowing is another important aspect to Seanchan culture. The higher
the status the person, the lower the bow they would receive. Bowing
to a person of the same status would simply be a nod to the other, while
bowing to a Lady of a House or someone higher, is done on the knees
while prostrating onto the floor. To the Empress, a full stomach bow
is required.
        Channeling is very taboo in the Seanchan culture. Anyone who
can channel is in danger of either death or permanent enslavement,
depending on the sex. If a male is found who can channel, he is killed
for fear that he will go mad and destroy property or lives. If a female
is found who can channel, she is linked to a sul'dam who holds an a'dam.
The girl is now a damane, a slave used for her abilities in furthering
the goals of the Empire.

See Also: SEANCHAN, SEANREQS, SEANRANKS, SEANRP
#0
SEANREQS

        The requirements to become a member of the Seanchan guild
are as follows.

1) Become level 20. This allows us to know that you consider your
character worth keeping and that you've spent at least some time on
him/her. It also ensures that newer people are at least familiar with how
the mechanics of the game works.

2) Send a background into the GuildLeader stating the following.
   Name
   Intended rank
   History of Character
   *The name of the GuildLeader can by found by the command wislist

3) You must gain at least 2 sponsors whom are guilded to gain admittance
into the guild.

See Also: SEANCHAN, SEANRANKS, SEANCULTURE, SEANRP
#0
SEANRANKS

                        \c14Military Ranks\c00
        These are the general ranks for those who are looking for a
military aspect of the Seanchan guild. Most people who wish to continue
on in the guild for ranks such as a morat or some other rank start here.

Soldier, Scout, Sergeant, Lieutenant, Captain, Field Commander,
Commander, General

                        \c14Morat Ranks\c00
        Morats are the men and women who ride the exotic and dangerous
animals of the Seanchan. They are highly trained not only in how to
make these animals behave and fight, but trained themselves in fighting
as well. The prefix der' is used to signify mastery of a certain exotic.

Morat'Raken, Der'Morat'Raken, Morat'To'Raken, Der'Morat'To'Raken,
Morat'Lopar, Der'Morat'Lopar, Morat'torm, Der'Morat'Torm, Morat'Grolm,
Der'Morat'Grolm, Morat'Corlm, Der'Morat'Corlm

                        \c14Slave Ranks\c00
        Slaves are an important part of the Seanchan culture. Most are
actually treated very well, as having a slave is relatively expensive
and an honor issue. Some slaves perform so well for their masters that
they are put above free men in their ranking, owned only by their masters
and the will of the Empress.

Slave, Honored Slave, So'jhin, Voice of the Blood

                        \c14General Ranks\c00
        These ranks are of the everyday citizens of the Seanchan
Empire who have gotten caught up in the whirl of activity. They could
be every day freemen, special spies in a house, a spy on the oathtaker,
a petty bureaucrat looking to get ahead, or even an Oathtaker, looking
for the stability Seanchan offers the rest of the people.

Oathtaker, Citizen, Listener, Spy, Bureaucrat

                        \c14Leashed/Leasher Ranks\c00
        These are the women whom the power of the Empire is based on.
Sul'dam control damane through the use of the a'dam, forcing the damane
to channel for the greater good of the Empire. The prefix der' indicated
mastery over the a'dam and damane (Type HELP A'DAM for information
on the leash itself).

Damane, Sul'dam, Der'sul'dam

                        \c14Nobility Ranks\c00
        The nobility are the leaders of the others in the guild. They
run the houses and make sure things are running smoothly. Nobility have
alot of responsibility to their house and making sure its goals are
being met.

Member of the Blood, Blooded Lord, Blooded Lady, Blooded High Lord,
Blooded High Lady

                        \c14Seeker Ranks\c00
        The Seekers for Truth in the Seanchan are a type of police. Owned
by the Empress, they are slaves only to her. They investigate matters
that might endanger the Empire, such as traitors or Darkfriends. They
hold much power, and are able to even put Nobility to the question if
they feel strongly about it.

Seeker for Truth, High Seeker for Truth

                        \c14DWG Ranks\c00
        The Deathwatch guard are the elite troops of the Empire and
serve the Empress. They are her property and do only her bidding.
They may be loaned to a house, but only to fulfill the needs of the
Empire. Trained from birth, they are the cream of the crop, willing
to die at a word and kill for a glance.

Deathwatch Guardsman
Sergeant of the Deathwatch Guard, Lieutenant of the Deathwatch Guard

See Also: SEANCHAN, SEANCULTURE, SEANREQS, SEANRP
#0
SEANRP

Role-playing in the Seanchan guild is quite a bit different than 
role-playing in other guilds. Life is very stratified and one almost
always obeys orders from those above them. Life is orderly and SC
society, and almost all from Seanchan like it that way. One must learn
quickly when to bow, and how much to bow before a higher ranked
person, and what to expect from other people's bows.

Life is strict, and life is hard. Most people who have come to fight
the oathbreakers know how to fight, and fight well. They have little
to no compassion for the lawless types who prey upon others or whom
consort with marath'damane.

There are always expceptions, but those people generally are viewed
with a suspicious mind by the other in SC.

A point to note is that Ogier in Seandar do not generally act like
the passive Ogier in the lands of Hawking. Here, Ogier are much more
fierce, and ready to do battle. They cannot be owned as slaves, but
often enter into the service of the military to future the might of
the Empire.

We welcome all who would like to enter the service of the Empire and
help make the lawless lands of Hawking a better place to live. We are
not all slavers bent on hurting as many people as we can. That is not
the goal of the Seanchan. The goal is to return the law and stability
that was lost after the death of Aurtur Hawking, in any means possible.
So come join us, you might be suprised.

See Also: SEANCHAN, SEANCULTURE, SEANRANKS, SEANREQS
#0
SHOPS SHOPKEEPERS

 Shops are places where the adventurer may purchase equipment for his quests,
and where he may sell his treasure if he should manage to survive the perils
with his life and sanity intact.  Many shops trade only in a specific type of
merchandise.  Thus, a baker may well refuse to buy your armor, even if it is
of high quality!

 To some people, the prospect of obtaining the entire inventory of a shop
by murdering the keeper may appear tempting - but beware: The shopkeepers
are often rugged, capable men; roughened by years of trading and, indeed,
surviving in a world where the only safe prospect is death in the end. Not
only that, killing or stealing from shopkeepers is considered \c02CHEATING\c00
and will not be tolerated by IMMortals. At All.

\c01See also: \c07BUY, SELL, LIST, VALUE\c00
#0
SKILLS

Depending on what class you have chosen, you can gain and train certain
skills (to see what skills are available to you, type "skills").
These skills are bought with Trains and trained with Practices, both
which you get when you increase in levels.
These skills can only be bought and trained at certain places where there
are trainer mobs, which are placed at certain spots throughout the mud.

If the skill in the "skills" list has an RP next to it instead of a level,
it means you need to be instructed that skill by someone else that has it.
#0
SPEARMASTERY BLADEMASTERY

Usage: Automatic

This questskill kicks in automatically once a fight begins.
It gives you +30 hitroll, +30 damroll and -10 AC.
#0
STATS

  The stats you have (Strength, Constitution, Dexterity, Intelligence,
Wisdom, Charisma, Hitpoints, Movement points, Mana points, the five flows)
are not set in stone. You can increase those if you have Trains, and this
is how you do it:
  Increasing Str, Con, Dex, Int, Wis, Cha, Hit, Move or Mana and the five
flows can be done at the proper trainer, which can be found at several
places.
  Just type the name of the stat, and if it is anything but the five flows
and you have Trains enough, you increase it by 1 (for Str, Con,
Dex, Int, Wis and Cha) or 10 (for Move, Mana and HP).

  Raising Move, Mana or Hp by 10 always costs 1 Train, the other stats cost
more the higher they are (1 per step up to 18, 2 up to 25, 3 up to 30).
Be careful not to use all the Trains for stats, they are used to buy
skills and spells as well.

The five flows (Air, Earth, Fire, Spirit and Water) cost Trains to 
raise as well, one to increase one of them by one step.

You gain Pracs and Trains when you reach a new level.

\c01See also:\c07 STATS2, TUTOR, ACHIEVE\c00
#0
A'DAM

  Device created by the Seanchan.  It is a ter'angreal:  a collar and
bracelet linked together by a leash, all of silver.  A woman who can be
taught to channel wear the bracelet and control the woman born with the
spark and wears the collar.  It creates a link between the two women.
When complete, the Sul'dam know what the Damane is doing with the Power.
The Damane can not channel without the Sul'dam permission or she will get
sick. The more Power she will draw without permission, the sicker she will
become.
  Both women are aware of the other's feeling, like anger, fear
and, sadness, although the Sul'dam can control what feelings are shared
through the leash.  The Sul'dam can make the Damane feel things through
the a'dam, like pain or pleasure. The Damane can not touch any weapon, nor
anything she think of as a weapon, or she will get sick.  The Damane can
not move the bracelet of the a'dam when no Sul'dam wears it.  The farther
she will try to move it, the sicker she will become, until unconsciousness.
  When a Damane and a Sul'dam are joined, whatever the Sul'dam feels, the
Damane feels ten times over, even to death.  It is why a Damane may never
strike at her Sul'dam, but she must protect her even more than herself.
If the leash of the a'dam is broken when a Damane and a Sul'dam wear the
a'dam, they die.  If a man who can channel touches the a'dam, both women
suffer, as if shocked, from the touch.  If a man who channels wears the
a'dam, he will die and so will the sul'dam if any, the listeners in the
Raven Tower use the A'dam as a questioning tactic, and torture.  A'dams
do not work on women that can not channel.

A'dam are restricted to the Seanchan guild. The only means of obtaining one
is to join the guild, or have a speical conference with the GL.
#0
TER'ANGREAL

Ter'angreals are as San'greals and Angreals, items of the One Power.
But, Ter'angreals doesn't increase the ammount of the One Power you
can channel. Instead, they're designed to use the One Power in a
special way. Examples of this are the stone ringg Egwene is given by
Verin to access Tel'aran'rhiod, or the balefire-producing rod stolen
by the Black Ajah.

Not as rare as *greals, Ter'angreals are still not very common, and
the White Tower will surely lay claim on it.

\c01See also:\c07 ANGREAL, SA'ANGREAL\c00
#0
"TOWER SEDAI"
Tower Aes Sedai Guild
=====================
     The Tower Aes Sedai guild is a roleplay guild, and hence, roleplay is
greatly emphasized within the guild.  Only the best roleplayers will be added
to the ranks of this guild.  If you are lucky enough to become a member of
the guild, you will most likely start as a Novice.  The basic rankings
most members will see are Novice, Accepted and Aes Sedai.  Those few who
are elected by their Ajahs may become Sitters in the Hall of the Tower,
or even Leader of their Ajah.  The Tower Aes Sedai guild also has places
for Protectorates (those who seek the Protection of the Tower, but either
do not channel, or do not wish to become Aes Sedai), and Prisoners (those
who the Tower takes as Prisoner for a period of time, for some
reason).
        A Novice's life is one of chores, learning, meekness,
duty and strict rules.  A Novice never speaks to an Aes Sedai, unless
spoken to first, and obeys an Aes Sedai's word without question (failing
to do so usually gets a sharp lecture from the Aes Sedai, which is all in
the spirit of roleplay!).  Novices are given instruction by Accepted and
Aes Sedai.  They are taught the basics of using the One Power; how to
grasp and release, identifying each of the five flows and how to weave
each of the five flows.  Novices are restricted to the White Tower, and
may not even enter the city of Tar Valon without an Aes Sedai's
permission as well as an escort (be it a Warder or an Aes Sedai).
***It is worth noting at this point that for RP purposes, a Novice may go
anywhere on the mud ICly, so as not to restrict RP, BUT, if caught by a
Warder or an Aes Sedai, such a Novice should *expect* to be *severely*
punished, ICly (ie, switchings, extra chores, or anything else an Aes
Sedai or the Amyrlin can think of!). When a Novice is deemed to have
suitable control of the One Power, and able to recognize the flows, weave
them to a certain aptitude and has the correct attitude, she is raised to
the Accepted.
        An Accepted's life is somewhat less confined by
rules than a Novice's, and they are allowed to choose their own areas of
study, within limits.  They also may not leave the White Tower without the
permission of an Aes Sedai as well as an escort (be it a Warder, Student,
Trainee or Aes Sedai).  An Accepted may speak to an Aes Sedai without
being spoken to first, but should always be respectful and meek (else face
rebuke by the Aes Sedai if she takes offense to the Accepted's tone!).
When an Accepted is deemed to have reached a suitable level of control,
knowledge, strength and skill in the One Power (and attitude) she is
raised to the Shawl.  Part of what an Accepted learns entails learning how
to weave complex weaves with the One Power, how to tie off weaves and
flows, history, and this on top of their chosen areas of study.
       When an Accepted is raised to the Shawl, she becomes Aes Sedai
and chooses her Ajah.  There are seven Ajahs:  the Red, the White, the
Green, the Grey, the Brown, the Yellow and the Blue, however only the
first six are present within the Tower Aes Sedai.  If you wish to become
Blue Ajah, best to seek out those darn Rebels! *grin*  An Aes Sedai may
do as she pleases, as long as it does not break Tower Law.  The Ajah an
Aes Sedai chooses tends to dictate what her actions will be as Aes Sedai,
and to what she will lend her energies for the course of her life.
Type HELP AJAH to learn about the Ajahs.
        A Sitter is an Aes Sedai who has been raised by her Ajah to the
Hall of the Tower - an esteemed position among Aes Sedai.
The Hall consists of three Sitters from each Ajah (all but the Blue in t
he case of the Tower Aes Sedai).  While the Amyrlin Seat
is by law the absolute power in the White Tower, in fact her power has
always depended on how well she could lead, manage or intimidate the Hall,
as there are many ways that the Hall can balk any Amyrlin's plans.  Thus,
a Sitter is an Aes Sedai who helps govern the White Tower, under the
Amyrlin and Keeper, and who holds some sway among all Aes Sedai.  Because
of this, Sitters are normally accorded a tad more respect over 'normal'
Aes Sedai (though not so much that they are revered).
        Ajah Leaders are those Aes Sedai that are elected by their Ajah
to lead that Ajah.  For each Ajah there is only one Ajah Leader, elected
by a majority vote (and incidentally they can be removed by a majority vote
among the Ajah). Within the Ajah, an Ajah Leader's word is as equal to the
Amyrlin's; outside of the Ajah, an Ajah Leader's word is simply that of
another Aes Sedai's.  Normally, no one outside of an Ajah will know that
Ajah's Leader, and normally the members of an Ajah will give the Leader
a title to show she is of some importance.
        Protectorates are people who seek the protection of the
Tower for a time.  They are usually not permanent members, and thus can
make for some interesting roleplay. Protectorates usually do not channel
(if they do, they may well find themselves bullied into becoming a Novice).
The Tower will offer protection to nearly anyone in need of it (OOCly, you
must clear this with the Tower Aes Sedai GL first, probably best done through
a mudmail stating your intentions, and roleplay with other Aes Sedai, or the
Tower Aes Sedai GL herself - though it may not be easy to get to see her 
ICly *wink*).
        Prisoners are those people Aes Sedai deem necessary to hold within
the walls of the White Tower for a period of time.  Again, this should be
cleared with the Tower Aes Sedai GL beforehand via a mudmail stating your 
intentions and why you want to be taken prisoner.  In the case of belonging 
to another guild, please check with your guild leader (GL) *before* mailing the
 
Tower Aes Sedai GL or beginning RP which may lead to you being taken prisoner. 
 
Of course, Prisoners do not *have* to be added to the guild - it may
simply be RP'd the whole way, if you wish.
        On the whole, however, the Tower Aes Sedai guild exists
for roleplay. We do not encourage leveling, though we do not restrict
it.  We *do* prefer our members to roleplay, however, and thus try to
create the best atmosphere for roleplaying.  Within the Tower, if you do
not agree with something ICly, then try to change it, ICly, by roleplaying
(this could be anything, from something an Aes Sedai is doing, or
something the Hall is considering, to something the Amyrlin is doing!).
If you love roleplay, then roleplay now fora position among the Tower Aes
Sedai - but read the requirements first!

See also:  AJAH, AES SEDAI
#0
WARDER GAIDIN

WARDER: (1)In the Old Tongue, "Gaidin", which means "Brother to Battles".
A warrior bonded to an Aes Sedai.  The bonding is a thing of the One Power:
By it he gains such gifts as quick healing, the ability to go long periods
without food, water, or rest, and the ability to sense the taint of the Dark
One at a distance.  So long as a Warder lives, the Aes Sedai to whom he is
bonded knows he is alive, however far away he is, and when he dies she will
know the moment and manner of his death.  The bonding seems weaker at a
distance, and the Warder knows precisely in what direction his Sedai lies in
relation to him.
While most Ajahs believe an Aes Sedai may have one Warder bonded to her at a
time, the Red Ajah refuses to bond any Warders at all, and the Green Ajah
believes an Aes Sedai may bond as many as she wishes.  Ethically, the Warder
must accede to the bonding voluntarily, but it has been known to be done
against the Warder's will.
What the Aes Sedai gain from the bonding is a closely held secret.

See Also: TWARDER, RWARDER
#0
TP "TRUE POWER"

The True Power
  Bestowed only by the blessing of the Dark One, this tremendous
source of power, is given only to Shai'tan's most trusted servants.
Being a weapon which cuts both ways, this power is drawn directly
from the Great Lord, rather than Saidin or Saidar. Its advantages
allow the wielder to use this dark energy independent of the One
Power, still being able to channel the horrific blessing even if
the wielder is severed from Saidin or Saidar. Besides being
extremely lethal, the True Power extracts a price from the
wielder as well, driving him or her to madness, much as the
taint on Saidin. The Saa, black dots that appear in one's eyes,
is the only known physical indicator of oncoming insanity.

SEE ALSO: Shai'tan, One Power 
#0
"TWO RIVERS"
Two Rivers is not its own country, but rather a part of Andor, though the
Two Rivers has not seen a taxman in five generations. Two Rivers shares
the western borderline with Tarabon, and the southern with Ghealdan. In
the  time up to the Trolloc Wars, however, the Two Rivers was known as
Manetheren, and was led by King Aemon, whose  home, then Aemon's Field,
over time became known as Emond's Field. Manetheren had a small but
extremely skilled army, and were often where the battle was fiercest, and
were known as the thorn in the Dark One's foot and the bramble in his
hand. Manetheren did not last, however - an attack on Manetheren of
unheard of proportions was intercepted by the Manetheren army that had
marched faster than a rested army, despite having little food and no sleep
for days. Promised reinforcements in three days if they could hold off an
attack that should have overwhelmed them in hours, Manetheren fell on the
tenth day - no reinforcements had arrived. King Aemon fell, but as his
wife felt Aemon die from within the safety of the Mountains of Mist with
the rest of the evacuated villagpeople, the Dark One's generals and
Dreadlords were engulfed by fire from within, (wife) channeling so much of
the Power as to kill herself as the Dark One's minions bruned in agony.
Not a single trolloc, fade or dreadlord that stepped foot on Manetheren
soil lived to escape, but Manetheren was gone.

However, Manetheren has been rediscovered in the Two Rivers, as the
manetheren blood is still strong, perhaps as strong as it was those many
years ago. Led by Lord Perrin 'Goldeneyes' Aybara and his beautiful, and
wife Lady Faile, Manetheren's flag was raised again, and the Two Rivers
once again is becoming the thorn in the Dark One's side; the bramble in
his hand.

\c14Geography:\c00
Bordered by the River Taren to the north, The White River (also known as
Manetherendrelle) and Forest of Shadows to the south, the Waterwood to the
east, and The West Wood, Sand Hills and Mountains of Mist to the west. The
main road runs north-south just east of the Westwood, starting at Taren
Ferry (on the River Taren) and continuing through Watch Hill, Emond's
Field and Deven Ride to the White River. From taren Ferry to Emond's Field
it is called the North Road. From Emond's Field to the White River, it is
called the Old Road. Heading west from Emond's Field into the Mountains
of Mist is Quarry Road, pathway to the Two Rivers' mines, aside from the
farming, the most important resources in the area. Emond's Field sits on
the Winespring, a natural fountain that flows east to form the miry Waterwood.

\c14Councils:\c00
Each village, from Taren Ferry on the River Taren, south  to Watch Hill,
Emond's Field and finally Deven Ride, which lies close to the White River,
is governed by the Village Council, a group of men with the town's Mayor
as leader, deciding and ruling the affairs of the village. Also in each
village is the Women's Circle, a similar group of women, who, amongst
other things, assist the village Wisdom, a woman with the ability to hear
the wind, though not all Wisdoms actually have this ability. The Village
Wisdom also knows much about healing, and herbs, medicines and cures, and
is the village's doctor.
Another job of the Women's Circle is to decide when a girl may braid her
hair; this signifies  girl's growing up into a woman. When a girl's hair
is braided, it means (amongst other things) that she is ready to marry,
though not required to do so. Before a couple can be married, they must be
betrothed (read: engaged) for one year. This is so the couple, and Women's
Circle can judge on whether the couple should be married.

\c14Festivals:\c00 Festival is the name given when refering to Winternight and 
Bel
Tine. Winternight celebrates the end of winter, and villagers go from
house to house, exchanging gifts and eating and drinking into the night.
The day following is Bel Tine, celebrating springtime. During Bel Tine
there are camp stories, singing and dancing, and occasionally fireworks or
even a gleeman. Bel Tine is also feast day, and a chance for everyone to
forget themselves in dance and song, something Two Rivers folk need little
excuse to do.

\c14People of Two Rivers:\c00 Two Rivers' people are of middling height, with
 dark
eyes, and dark hair. Consisting mainly of farmers (wool and tabac the main
'crops'), Two Riversmen are strong and stubborn to the bone. Though
winters are long ard cold, with deep snow that can damage crops, this
seldom stops them from continuing on with their lives. When they are
knocked over, they take little time worrying before standing up and
starting again, which gave birth to the saying "If times are tough, then
light willing, we'll get through, and if the light isn't willing, we'll
get through anyway." This never-say-die attitude is thanks partly to the
blood of Manetheren, which is still strong in the people of Two Rivers.
This trait runs throughout all Two Riversmen, though people from Taren
Ferry have a reputation for slyness and trickery, and there are two
families, the Coplins and the Congars, who are known as whiners and
trouble-makers.
Recently, many refugees have come to the Two Rivers, as it is a relatively
safe place in a world that seems on the brink of collapse.
#0
TUATHA'AN TINKERS

Greetings Friends, allow me to guide you through the information about
the Tuatha'an. First things first, I will show you a little about the
Tuatha'an culture and beliefs. A typical Tinker camp consists of a
number of brightly colored wagons, brightly clothed people, music,
laughter, and song, as if the inhabitants are having a celebration.
The Tinkers themselves strive to have a happy life; occupationally
they are usually singers, dancers, musicians, and especially artisans
and craftsman. The Tinkers are nomadic; their camps never settle in
one place for long, for they must always travel in search of the
Song and to spread peace known as the Way of the Leaf. They travel
in large wagons built to act as homes or crafting shops. The latter
are reinforced and more than twice the weight of a normal wagon,
the Tinkers having found a way to hold larger tools of the craft
such as forges and spits. Crafting is not only with metal, however,
as the Tuatha'an also find themselves tailoring clothing, setting
jewelry, or even mending sails.

The Tuatha'an have a very unique view on life called the Way of the Leaf.
This lifestyle is pacifistic; a Tuatha'an would rather run than fight.
It is believed that violence not only causes harm and injury to the victim,
but also to the attacker, and so a Tuatha'an will run not in fear but to
not hurt his aggressor. Within the camp, visitors are quietly asked to remove
their weapons out of respect to the Way. This lifestyle is strange to most
of the rest of the world in the day and age of strife, yet the Tinkers travel
through it with optimism. Their quiet, happy ways tend to draw many people
away from the villages they past, and for such, the Tuatha'an are often
called Child Stealers and shunned from towns despite the craftwork they
can help do.

The main goal of the Tinkers is not to convert everyone to pacifism, but
to find the long lost Song. It is believed that when the Song is found
peace will simply return to the lands. And so they dedicate their lives
traveling from place to place in search, helping all they can along the way.
For further information about the Guild, read the Requirement board and
speak with as many Tuatha'an as you can. The Mahdi (Guildleader) is also
always happy to answer any questions you may have.

See Also: "WAY OF THE LEAF", TINKERREQS
#0
TINKERREQS

You may wish to read the Guild Requirement board at Recall in order to
see a more detailed description of each of these:
1. A belief in pacifism
2. A background sent to the Guildleader
3. A description that resembles a Tuatha'an
4. Any level, preferrably level 1, as Tinkers do not kill
5. 3 sponsors who mail their sponsorship to the GL
   (less if the guild is small. Check with the GL)

Note that if you have a character from another guild or mud location and
later choose to follow the Way of the Leaf for IC reasons, come roleplay
with the Tuatha'an, and it will be decided if you can stay.

See Also: TINKERS, "WAY OF THE LEAF"
