GUILDEQ GEQ

The following rules govern the creation of guild equipment on Dragon's Fang:

&g1.&n You must first read and be conversant with the stated builder policy, 
listed under '&rpolicy building&n'.

&g2.&n The Head Builder must be notified of any changes made to existing geq,
and the creation of new geq, BEFORE such changes are made.  The Head GL should
also be made aware of the creation of new geq, though the final say on 
specific stats remains the prerogative of the HB.

&g3.&n The rules for stats are as follows; these may be altered by the Head 
Builder as deemed appropriate:

	&Ra.&n You have a total of &y1500&n points with which to buy stats for
each set of geq.  No player may have more than 1500 points of geq in his or
her possession at any time.

	&Rb.&n Each point of AC costs &y1&n point (max: &c200&n).
	&Rc.&n Each point of hitroll/damroll costs &y10&n points per PAIR (max: &c50/50&n).
	&Rd.&n Each +stat costs &y10&n points (max of &c4&n per stat).
	&Re.&n Each bonus hit point costs &y1&n point (max: &c300&n).
	&Rf.&n Each point of ABS costs &y2&n (max: &c200&n).
	&Rg.&n Each point of bonus mana or movement costs &y1&n point (max: &c500&n for
	   each).
	&Rh.&n Angreal prices are &y10&n points per 1% (max: &c50%&n).
	&Ri.&n Weapon costs depend on the damage dice used.  The following
	   are permissible:
		each 1d6 = &y20&n points (max: &c15&n)
		each 1d8 = &y25&n points (max: &c12&n)
		each 1d10 = &y30&n points (max: &c10&n)
	&Rj.&n Each extra attack costs &y200&n points (max: &c3&n)>
	&Rk.&n Special eq, such as autohide Warder cloaks, have a base cost
	   of &y100&n points, before added stats.
	&Rl.&n Permanent lights are free; containers are also free, but should 
	   have capacities no greater than 10000.
	&Rm.&n Players are limited to no more than 1 container and 1 angreal.
	   The SA'ANGREAL flag may not be set.
	&Rn.&n All geq should be flagged as !SELL, !DROP, and !BREAK.  It is
	   at the discretion of individual GL's to determine if the !TOOL
	   flag should be set.
	&Ro.&n You may not create eq that impacts negatively on one or more
	   stats, such as eq that gives -5 str.    
	&Rp.&n No item may have fewer than 200, or more than 500 points on it
	   for any reason.  Also, you must give out at least 4 pieces of 
	   geq.

Try to keep eq realistic: if you guildweapon is a dagger, then it probably
should not be D_WIELD.  Similarly, descing finger eq to be a pair of pants
is cause for reconsideration.

&gExample:&n Joe the GL creates a set of geq that gives 3 xattacks, 50/50,
and has a 10d6 weapon.  He needs to spend 3*200 + 10*50 + 10*20 = 600 + 500 +
200 = 1300 points.  He now has 200 points left over to spend as he wishes,
keeping in mind the maxes listed above.  Left over points are wasted, so you
are advised to use all 1500.
#200
ADVANCE

Usage: advance <victim> <level>

ADVANCE moves a player to a new level.  If used to promote a player to an
immortal level, and if you have the autowiz program installed, the wizlist and
immlist will automatically be recreated.

Example:

  > advance rasmussen 34

See also: SET
#200
AUTHORIZATION AUTHORIZE UNAUTHORIZATION UNAUTHORIZE

Usage: authorize <name>
       unauthorize <name>

AUTHORIZE declares a player's name is acceptable for Dragon's Fang. Until
new players have their names authorized by an Immortal, they cannot leave
the newbie area.
UNAUTHORIZE does the reverse, in case some mistake took place.

Example:

   > authorize Sorilea
   > unauthorize DarkMachineOfDeath

See also: AUTHCHECK.
#200
AUTHCHECK

Usage: authcheck

AUTHCHECK searches every character on for unauthorized names. Cases of
level one (suspected real newbies) and over it (usually established
characters who happen to be without the flag set to on) are displayed
seperately.

Also see: AUTHORIZE, UNAUTHORIZE.
#200
Multi

Usage: multi

Multi searches through the userlist for IPs that match and reports them,
enabling you to find multiplayers.
#200
BUGCHECK

Usage: bugcheck [-f|<zone number>]

This little command does the following:
Goes through all the objects in the mud and looks for those that have
excessive stats, "unfinished" in their descriptions or simply lack
descriptions.
Goes through all the rooms in the mud and checks whether they have exits
leading back to the same room (recursive exits), exits leading nowhere,
or no exits, and also whether the room descriptions contain the word
"unfinished".

If you type -f as argument, a detailed list of all errors is saved to 
file, if you type a zone vnum as argument, it gives a short list of 
what's wrong in that zone. You cannot combine -f and zone number.
#200
CLONE

Usage: clone <object>

CLONE duplicates an object, keeping tooled descs, obj affections and
all intact. It does not clone contents, though.
#200
GUILDINVIS
Usage: guildinv

   GUILDINVIS toggles your status of guild invisible from on to off.
Holylight negates it completely, and it can be combined with normal
wizinvis.
   While you are guild-invisible, only mortals in the same guild
as you (or, if you are unguilded, only non-guilded mortals) can
see you.

\c01ALSO SEE:\c00 invis.
#200
SUBRANK

Usage: subrank <person> <subrank>

SUBRANK sets a player's subrank. There is a common set of subranks for all
the guilds, to see the set which is available type "srank".

Example:

  > subrank Narsil Sitter

See also: GSET
#200
WIZAT

Usage: at <room VNUM | item | mob | player name> <command> <arguments>

AT can be used to perform an action in a location other than where you are
standing.  The first argument can be a virtual room number or the name of a
character or object.  The remainder of the line is passed to the command
interpreter.

Examples:

  > at 3001 look
  > at fido kill fido
  > at 3.corpse get all corpse
  > at catje wave catje

See also: GOTO
#200
AWARD

Usage: award <victim> <amount>

Awards a player with <amount> Quest points.
#200
BAN UNBAN

Usage: ban [<all | new | select> <site>]
       unban <site>

These commands prevent anyone from a site with a hostname containing the
site substring from logging in to the game.  You may ban a site to ALL, NEW
or SELECT players.  Banning a site to NEW players prevents any new players
from registering.  Banning a site to ALL players disallows ANY connections
from that site.  Banning a site SELECTively allows only players with site-ok
flags to log in from that site.  Ban with no argument returns a list of
currently banned sites.

Unban removes the ban.

Examples:

  > ban all whitehouse.gov
  > unban ai.mit.edu

See also: WIZLOCK
#200
DATE

Shows the current real time. (Not a social)
#200
DC

Usage: dc <descriptor number>

DC (DisConnect) is used to disconnect a socket.  If used on a playing socket,
the player will lose his/her link, but, unlike PURGE, will not extract the
player or dump the player's inventory on the ground.

DC is also useful for disconnecting people who have accidentally left
themselves at the main menu, or connections sitting in the "Get name" state.

See also: USERS
#200
ECHO GECHO QECHO SEND

Usage: echo <message>
       gecho <message>
       send <victim> <message>
       qecho <message>

ECHO displays a string to everyone in your room.
GECHO displays the string to everyone in the game.
QECHO displays the string to everyone with the QUEST flag.
SEND displays the string to a particular person.

C-style line breaks can be used to create paragraphs in GECHO.
Just use the \n between two sentences. You can also use \t for tabs.

ie: gecho Du gamla du fria,\ndu fjallhoga nord.\nOsv, i all oandlighet.

Yields:
Du gamla du fria,
du fjallhoga nord.
Osv, i all oandlighet.

Other Examples:

  > echo Hi, everyone in the room.
  > gecho Hi, everyone in the game, isn't this annoying?
  > send rasmussen You are being watched.
#200
FORCE

Usage: force <victim | all> <command> <arguments>

FORCE forces a character, either monster or player, to perform a certain
action.  FORCE ALL forces everyone in the game; FORCE ROOM forces everyone in
your room.

Example:

  > force fido drop meat
  > force all save
  > force room look fido

If you are invisible to the one being forced, the force will be performed
silently.
#200
FREEZE THAW

Usage: freeze <victim>
       thaw <victim>

FREEZE, originally invented here at CircleMUD (we think), is used to prevent
a player from playing.  If frozen, the game will ignore all commands entered
by the player, including QUIT, until the player is unfrozen with THAW.

Obviously, this command should only be used in extreme disciplinary
circumstances.

See also: SET -> FROZEN
#200
GOTO TRANS TELEPORT

Usage: goto <location>
       trans <victim>
       teleport <victim> <location>

These commands are used to transports yourself and others to different rooms.
GOTO allows you to go to other rooms; TRANS transports a person from wherever
they are to the room YOU are in; TELEPORT transports your victim to some other
location.

For both GOTO and TELEPORT, the location specifier can be either a virtual
room number, or the name of a character or object.

Examples:

  > goto 3001
  > goto rasmussen
  > trans fido
  > teleport fido 3001
  > teleport fido 2.fido

See also: POOFIN, POOFOUT, SET -> ROOM, WIZAT
#200
HANDBOOK

Usage: handbook

Guidelines for having an Immortal character -- you should read it.
#200
HASSLE NOHASSLE 

Usage: nohassle

Toggles a flag to prevent aggressive monsters from attacking.
#200
NEWFORM
------
\c01Description:\c00 This is what the design stage of our forms
system has led to. It seems to be well defined, robust and complete
enough, covering the goals we set and complimenting the rest of the
fighting system Stefan has designed.
   Please don't let any details of this slip to the mortals or anyone
outside the MUD.
------
GOALS: Combat system more elaborate internally, with as much
       invisible to the player as possible. All attributes
       and stats used where they apply. Robust forms system,
       applicable to non-sword forms. Everything is a form,
       either RJ-type for sword wielders, or more descriptive
       for other weapons i.e "a vertical thrust at the shoulder" .

============================================================
Dictionary:
	SF: Speed Factor.
	StartPos, EndPos: Starting Position, Ending Position.
	PC: Priority Counter.
============================================================

Continued in NEWFORM1
#200
NEWFORM1

1.1: Basic one-on-one fight.
     ----------------------
      If we can agree that the best forms are the more complex ones
(i.e. a form may cause great damage, but it takes a while to execute
it, prepare it, etc), then we go back to the Form's Speed factor.
Each of those can be a number from 0 to 1 - the smaller the number,
the slower the form.
      When a form is used, set its counter to 0, as Stefan suggested.
      The -rest- of the forms only get their priority counters
increased if a check is made according to its speed (that also
represents its complexity factor) - an actual IC thing!
      I.e. in the Second Round above, say that:
              River has been set to 0, since it was just used.
              Mountain has a Speed Factor 0.32 (it's pretty good)
              Parry has a Speed Factor of 1 - it's the basic one, it
                      sucks. :) but it's damn fast in preparing.
              So, Parry's Priority Counter  gets a chance of 1 to get
increased (always does) while Mountain only has a 0.32 chance to
be increased, so it gets upgraded one round in three.

      So, let's say Kane is a wise-ass. He knows Mountain is pretty
good, and wants to use just that.
      He's in trouble. :) Its counter will only upgrade one every three
rounds, and then it will be probably not be chosen that round either
since Parry will have a counter of 3 by then (well, on average).
      .. And if Kane is lucky, well, he can get to see his Great Form
used 2-3 times in a row.. it's just highly unlikely. :)
      Another form, not as good as Mountain could have a Priority
Counter of 0.9 for example.. etc. So it will be used pretty often,
almost as much as any other - and Parry won't really be used TOO
often :) With say, 10 forms to choose from, even if Parry's individual
chances of being picked up are highest than any other single form's,
it's going to be more likely that one of the others is picked. And it will
be set to 0 when it's used once, anyway.
      I think this one is it, unless you guys can break it somehow. :)
And good thing is, we don't even need any other rotations after
it (re-using forms from fastest-to-slowest, etc) since it's all integral
here.
      Having a form's percentage higher (or maybe having skills
like Blademastery) could possibly add something to the chances of
a form's Priority Counter being increased.
      Of course, experimentation will tell us what the numbers
we should be using here should be. But I think it works.

1.2: Addition: Specific body parts attacked/defended.
     --------
	Kane has three forms: River, Mountain, and Parry.

River has
	a SF of 0.5 (pretty good)
	StartPos/EndPos: Crouching/Crouching.
Mountain has
	a SF of 0.25 (pretty damn good)
	StartPos/EndPos: Standing/Standing
Parry has
	a FS of 1
	StartPos/EndPos: Standing/Standing

	Stefan has three forms: Whack, Smack, and Slash.

Whack has
	a SF of 0.5
	StartPos/EndPos: Standing/Kneeling (i.e. attacks legs)
Smack has
	a SF of 0.25
	StartPos/EndPos: Crouching/Standing (i.e. attacks body)
Slash has
	a SF of 1
	StartPos/EndPos: Standing/Standing (i.e. attacks body)

QUESTION: Do we fix it so that for the basic forms StartPos
and EndPos doesn't matter, i.e. they are always eligible? I let it
stand that they are Standing/Standing in this example, but I made
the code allow them to start at any position. Why? Check
round 2; only one form is eligible there normally, simply because
Slash isn't a Crouching StartPos form. But there are Crouching
Slashes, ICly.

(both people are standing when combat begins)
(Stefan always wins initiative)
FIRST ROUND :
	All have a priority of 0 at first.
	Each form is at priority 0, no form at more than that,
so they can all be picked.

(Sorilea's idea):
	The code looks for a form for Stefan and Kane: A list is
created with all forms having a Standing StartPos.
	Whack and Slash fit. Whack is chosen for Stefan (50% chance).
	Mountain and Parry fit. Mountain is chosen for Kane (50% chance).

	Whack attacks legs; Mountain defends body; Stefan has
a better than normal chance of succeeding because of this.
	(NOTE: Stefan, can you add form vs form to the list of factors
affecting a successful blow?)

	Parry and Slash's PCs are incremented. (at 1)
	Smack's 0.5 PC is incremented. (at 1)
	River's 0.5 PC isn't incremented. (at 0)
	Whack and Mountain's PCs  are set to zero anyway.

(Kane is standing; Stefan is Crouching)
SECOND ROUND:
	The code looks for a form for Stefan and Kane: A list is
created: the attacker's stuff are always chosen first. (in the last
round, it was the first round, so it was easier since everyone was
standing).
	We are looking for a form for Stefan, StartPos Crouching.
Making a list:
	Smack and Slash are eligible. Slash is chosen.
We are looking for a form for Kane, StartPos Standing.
Making a list:	
	Parry is eligible. Actually, it's the only form with a PC
over 1, so it would be chosen anyway.
	
	Slash attacks body; Parry defends body; 	no penalties
due to different defending positions.
	
	Slash, Parry's PCs are set to 0.
	Smack (with FS of 0.5) is actually incremented again : 2
	River (with FS of 0.5) is incremented this time: 1
	Mountain at 0.25 and Whack at 0.5's PCs aren't incremented.

Continued in NEWFORM2
#200
NEWFORM2

2.0 Group fighting.
    --------------
        Forms combat, no one guy is the tank.
	Now, there is one requirement so far from Sori; to try and
have it as little tank-based (only one person gets attacked in each
group at a time) as possible.
	There are a few ways to handle this: I will give two.

2.1 Formations.
	Easily the best of all I've seen, but it was
be a b*tch to come up with, so bear with me. Now, this is derived from
Medievia, by yours truly. It's taking me a while to think, and correct me
if I leave anything out. It's different in some ways.
	Each person in a group has a place in a formation. The further
one is behind another person, the less likely he is to be hit. There are
three "slots" in each row.
	
	The first "line" (i.e. people who aren't covered by someone
in front of them) get chosen to be attacked 50% of the time. The
second "line" (people with just one person in front of them in the
formation) gets attacked 30% of the time, and the last line (the
ones with two people in front of them in the formation) get
hit 20% of the time. (you know, when the formation temporarily
breaks under an assault, or during the chaos of combat and
someone gets through , people protected still end up being attacked)
	Notice that if you are just standing in the third row of the
formation without someone in front of you, it's the same thing
as standing in the front, i.e. you are considered to be in a row
depending on how many people there are in front of you.
	The formula is (line percentage) * (persons in the row) / 3
to calculate anyone's chances of being damaged.

(	There is a command (in Medievia's case groupform) that
brings up something like this:

|    Kane         Stefan         3   |
|    Narsil        Fredrik        6   |
|    Kirene                8         9   |

	
for easier access and tactics. The tactics of this, by the way, are
excellent - think group weaves, where the impact of a fireball
is less as the distance increases from the front.
	You get in an empty slot simply by typing gset 8 (for example)
to be in the third row, second slot.)
	And, as we say, this is -it-. In every round, there simply
-is- no initiative common for all the group like in the other
systems (where someone is the tank, one group wins initiative
and attacks, the other defends).
	Initiative is first calculated for everyone in the combat.
	The fastest person picks opponent according to the percentages
above (yes, so two can end up attacking one person! you may
notice the percentages don't end up to 100%, and why should they?)
like this:
	First, the row attacked will be chosen. 50% for the first,
30% for the second, 20% for the third. Empty rows aren't considered,
only ones with someone in them.
	Remember that a row is defined by how many people are
standing in front of you, the visual example of groupform above is
just that - a visual.
	Then, the person in that row is chosen depending on the
number of people in it. For example, each person in the second
row above has a 50% chance of being attacked. Kirene, being alone
in the third row, has an 100% chance if her 20% row is chosen to be
attacked.
	The person who is chosen this way has automatically lost
initiative. And we continue going down the number of people in the
group until everyone has an opponent. Yes, it is possible for player A
to have rolled a better initiative than player B, and still be defending
while player B is free to attack - if he was attacked by someone yet
faster than him, player C. - he was "intercepted" although he
was faster than the other guy - combat in large numbers is like that.
	I think this covers everything. Encourages tactics, there is no
one tank, it is -very- simple to use by a player (it is just one command,
gset <slot>, and one to see the group formation with groupform),
it encourages tactics although doesn't -force- it (people will never have
to type either command; if they are ungrouped they are in the first
row anyway, and if they don't use it while grouping, well, then they
are unorganized and that's bad, but that's pretty realistic.
	It handles individual combat like group combat with one person
in each group. It does limit groups to nine people maximum, but ermm. :)
Plus we can increase it easily, I just don't think it's necessary.
	Well, there it is. The beauty of it is that it's pretty easy to code,
I think. The algorithm for choosing an opponent is included in this
example, and all it really needs is a 3x3 array for each group to keep
the positions. Or maybe the other way around, an unsigned int for each
player showing his place in a group. Anyway, you get the drift.

2.2 Individual initiative.
        This is the cop-out. Forms combat, no one guy is the tank.
	Everything is the same as before, initiative is rolled at the
beginning of combat. A list is created like before, from fastest to slowest.
	The fastest person choses one person at random from the other
group, that person automatically loses initiative. You can indeed end
up attacking someone who's already under attack.

2.3 Comments/comparisons between schemes:
	Scheme 2.2 is straight forward. Yet we'd have to keep commands like
rescue,etc that are just futile in the last scheme, and we can't do an "impact"
of a weave that'd look really cool (with more damage from an area
weave to the front rows and less to the back) as with 2.1. Plus, you could
do some -great- Band guildskills with formations. :) But on the other hand
this is a lot simpler.
#200
GSET

Usage: gset <player> <rank>

This command sets the rank within the guild for a player.
Can only be used on guilded players.

Also see: SUBRANK
#200
GUILD

Usage: guild <player> <guildname>

This command makes a player join a guild at the lowest rank.
#200
HOLYLIGHT

Usage: holylight

A toggle which allows you to see:
   Invisible people and objects, even if you don't have 'detect invisibility'
   Hidden people, even if you don't have 'sense life'
   Dark rooms, even if you don't have a light

It is expected most immortals will keep HOLYLIGHT on most of the time;
it exists so that you have the ability to see what mortals see for
debugging purposes.
#200
IMOTD

Usage: imotd

Displays the Immortal message of the day.  This file usually contains
new information on commands recently added, new features and other
important information that immortals should be aware of.

See also: MOTD
#200
INVIS

Usage: invis [level]

INVIS sets your invisibility level.  With no argument, invis toggles between
making you fully visible and fully invisible.  If you specify a level, only
people at and above the level you specify will be able to see you.

Examples:

  > invis
  > invis 31

See also: VISIBLE
#200
LAST

Usage: last <player_name>

For checking the last time a person logged on, their sitename, and their
ID number.

Example:

  > last ras
  [  24] [14 Cl] Ras          : somesite.edu : Tue May 16 22:07:09 1995

See also: STAT
#200
LOAD

Usage: load <mob | obj> <virtual number>

LOAD is used to create mobiles and objects.  The first argument specifies if
you are trying to load a mobile or an object; the second is the virtual
number.

Example:

  > load obj 3099
  You create a bulletin board.

  > load mob 3005
  You create the receptionist.

See also: VNUM
#200
MEDIT

Usage: medit <vnum>
       medit save <zone>

Edits an existing or creates a new mobile in the database. This command makes
you enter a menu driven OLC system.

The second alternative makes you save your changes onto disk.

See MEDIT2 for a description of the menu options.

See also: OEDIT, REDIT, SEDIT, ZEDIT
#200
MEDIT2

When you type medit, you see the following screen:

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
&g1&n) Sex: &yNeutral&n                 &g2&n) Alias: &ymob unfinished&n
&g3&n) S-Desc: &ythe unfinished mob&n
&g4&n) L-Desc:-
&yAn unfinished mob stands here.&n
&g5&n) D-Desc:-
&yIt looks, err, unfinished.&n
&g6&n) Level:       [  &c0&n],  &g7&n) Alignment:    [   &c0&n]
&g8&n) Hitroll:     [  &c0&n],  &g9&n) Damroll:      [   &c0&n]
&gA&n) NumDamDice:  [  &c1&n],  &gB&n) SizeDamDice:  [   &c1&n]
&gC&n) Num HP Dice: [  &c1&n],  &gD&n) Size HP Dice: [ &c100&n],  &gE&n) HP Bonus: [    &c0&n]
&gF&n) Armor Class: [&c100&n],  &gG&n) Exp:     [        &c0&n],  &gH&n) Money: [       &c0&n]
&gI&n) Position   : &yStanding&n
&gJ&n) Default    : &yStanding&n
&gK&n) Attack     : &yhit&n
&gL&n) NPC Flags  : &yISNPC&n 
&gM&n) AFF Flags  : &yNOBITS&n 
&gN&n) SKILL Flags: &yNOBITS&n 
&gO&n) Mob programs
&gQ&n) Quit
Enter choice : 
-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

Here is a description of the function of each entry:

1. &ySex&n: Self-explanatory, but do not fail to set.  Neutral gendered 
        Aes Sedai and female Asha'man look rather strange.
2. &yAlias&n: The list of keywords that denote the mob, separated by spaces.  
          To look at the mob, for example, you would type 'look <keyword>'.
3. &yS-Desc&n: This is the name you see when communicating or fighting with 
           the mob.  Example: <S-Desc> scratches you.  Keep as brief, but
           as descriptive, as possible.
4. &yL-Desc&n: What the player sees when looking at the mob.  You should
           include some sort of description as to what the mob is doing. For
           example, "<name of mob> is sitting on a stool, sharpening a wicked
           looking knife."
5. &yD-Desc&n: This is the description a player sees when looking at the mob,
           similar to the description of a player character.  Do not ignore
           this entry, even if you do not wish to be overly verbose, as the
           default entry is "It looks, err, unfinished."
6. &yLevel&n : The level of the mob.  Set between 1 and 199.
7. &yAlignment&n: This field is no longer used.  Do not set.
8. &yHitroll&n: How much the mob's chance of hitting its opponent increases. 
            Each point of hitroll increases this chance by 1%.
9. &yDamroll&n: The amount of extra damage the mob does per successful hit.
A. &yNumDamDice&n: Amount of dice worth of damage the mob does per hit.
B. &ySizeDamDice&n: Size of the dice of damage the mob does.  Together with 
                fields A and 9, this determines the total amount of damage
                the mob does with every hit.  For example, the mob might do
                10d12+15 damage, where 10 is NumDamDice, 12 is SizeDamDice,
                and 15 is the damroll.  This would correspond to 25-135 
                points of damage per hit.
C. &yNumHPDice&n: Amount of hit point dice the mob has.
D. &ySizeHPDice&n: The size of the hit point dice the mob has.
E. &yHP Bonus&n: How many extra hit points the mob has.  This works with 
             fields C and D to determine the total number of hit points the
             mob has, analogous to the damage calculation.  Hence, a mob might
             have 10d50+100 hit points, with 10 the NumHPDice, 50 the 
             SizeHPDice, and 100 the HP Bonus, for a total of 150-600 HP.
F. &yArmor Class&n: The armor class of the mob.  The lower it is, the harder
                it is to hit.
G. &yExp&n: How much experience an equally levelled character gets for killing
        the mob.
H. &yMoney&n: The number of coins the mob carries.
I. &yPosition&n: The position the mob gets loaded into the game with (e.g.,
             sitting or standing).
J. &yDefault&n: The position the mob goes to after zone resetting.
K. &yAttack&n: The type of message the mob's attacks give, such as hit or stab.
L. &yNPC flags&n: A list of specifications the mob's characteristics, defined
              as follows.

        &gSPEC&n: Do not set.
        &gSENTINEL&n: The mob stays in the room it's loaded to and never moves.
        &gSCAVENGER&n: The mob picks up any item of value that's on the ground.
        &gISNPC&n: The default.  Must always be present.
        &gAWARE&n: Mob cannot be basckstabbed.
        &gAGGR&n: The mob attacks any visible player in the room without
              provocation.
        &gSTAY-ZONE&n: The mob can move from room to room, but will not leave
                   the zone to which it was loaded.
        &gWIMPY&n: The mob flees combat when its hitpoints drop below 25%.
        &gMOUNT&n: The mob can be used as a horse.  Currently not supported.
        &gUNUSED&n: Do not set.
        &gTRACKER&n: The mob will hunt down any player that flees from a fight
                 with it.
        &gMEMORY&n: The mob remembers players that attacked it and fled, and
                will attack them on sight.
        &gHELPER&n: The mob assists any mob that is being attacked by a
                player in the same room.
        &g!CHARM&n: The mob cannot be charmed by any means.
        &g!SUMMN&n: Unused, do not set.
        &g!SLEEP&n: The mob is immune to the weave sleep.
        &g!BASH&n: The mob cannot be affected by the bash skill.
        &g!BLIND&n: The mob cannot be affected by the dirt kick skill.
        &g!TRIP&n: The mob cannot be tripped.
        &g!STUN&n: The mob cannot be stunned.
        &gHUMAN&n: The mob is human. Can be set, but doesn't really do 
               anything yet.
        &gSHADOWSPAWN&n: The mob is Shadowspawn.  See HUMAN.
        &gCHANNELER&n: The mob can channel.  See HUMAN.

M. &yAFF Flags&n: The flags that determine what the mob is affected by.  A
              description of each follows.

        &gBLIND&n: The mob is blind.
        &gINVIS&n: The mob is invisible to normal sight.
        &gUNUSED&n: Do not set.
        &gSUFFOCATING&n: The mob is drowning/choking.  Normally not set.
        &gDET_INVIS&n: The mob can see invisible characters.
        &gSENSE_LIFE&n: The mob can see hidden characters.
        &gWRAPPED&n: The mob is wrapped in Air.
        &gRUNNING&n: The mob is running (an Aiel guild skill).
        &gGAGGED&n: The mob is gagged with Air.
        &gINFRA&n: The mob can see in DARK rooms.
        &g!TRACK&n: The mob cannot be tracked.
        &gHIDE&n: The mob is hidden.
        &gCAMOUFLAGED&n: Essentially the same as HIDE.
        &gVEILED&n: The mob is veiled like an Aiel.

All other flags that appear should not be set.

N. &ySkill flags&n: These flags determine the combat skills the mob has. The
                available ones are bash, kick, trip, dirtkick, disarm, and 
                stun.
O. &yMob programs&n: See the helpfile 'mobprogs'.
Q. &yQuit&n: This option exits the medit editor.  You will be asked if you
want to save changes to the mob.  If you select no, then your changes are
deleted.  If you select yes, your changes are only saved until the next
crash or reboot.  To save them permanently, you must type 'medit save 
<zonenum>.' 
#200
MOBPROGS MOBPROGRAMS MOB
Mob programs are simple scripts that can be written, using a menu driven
olc system, to allow mobs greater functionality and interaction with their 
environment.  Selecting option O in the medit menu brings up the following
screen:

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
&gMain term:     
 -----Sideterms-----&n
   <none>

&g -----Actions----- &n
   &R<none>&n
(&yD&n)elete (&yE&n)xit (&yM&n)ainterms (&yS&n)ideterms (&yA&n)ctions (&yN&n)ew 
Enter choice
-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

&gD&n deletes the current mob program listed.
&gE&n exits the mob program menu and takes you back to the normal medit menu.
&gM&n changes/adds the mainterm of the trigger.
&gS&n changes/adds/removes the sideterms of the trigger.
&gA&n changes/adds/removes the actions to be run when the program is triggered.
&gN&n creates a new mob program.

Typing M, S, or A presents you with another menu, allowing you to pick whatever
conditions and actions you want met/performed.  Do not select actions until 
you have chosen a mainterm; if you do, the actions will be deleted when a
mainterm is selected.  Note that you may place more than one mob program on
a single mob, though the maximum is 30.

If you wish the mob to emote certain actions, the following variables may
be used in the expression:

        &y$N&n: the name of the target
        &y$n&n: the name of the mob
        &y$E|$e&n: he/she/it (target|mob)
        &y&S|$s&n: his/hers/its (target|mob)
        &y$M|$m&n: him/her/it (target|mob)

For example, typing "$n grins at $N and motions to $M" would emote
"<mob name> grins at <playername> and motions to him" (assuming the player
is male).  
#200
MUTE

Usage: mute <victim>

MUTE is used to shut a player up.  When muted, a player will not be able to
use most communication channels until he/she is unmuted.

See also: FLAGS
#200
NOHASSLE HASSLE

Usage: nohassle

Toggles a flag to prevent aggressive monsters from attacking.
#200
NOTITLE

Usage: notitle <vicitim>

Prevent players from being able to set their own titles; i.e., if the
player consistently has an offensive title.  The definition of offensive
is left as an exercise for the reader.

See also: TITLE
#200
NOWIZ

Usage: nowiz

Allows you to hear or ignore messages coming over the wiznet.

See also: WIZNET
#200
OEDIT

Usage: oedit <vnum>
       oedit save <zone>

Edits an existing or creates a new object in the database. This command makes
you enter a menu driven OLC system.

The second alternative makes you save your changes onto disk.

See OEDIT2 for a description of the menu options.

See also: MEDIT, REDIT, SEDIT, ZEDIT
#200
OEDIT2

When you type oedit, you will see the following screen:

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
Item number : [&c32680&n]
&g1&n) Namelist : &yunfinished object&n
&g2&n) S-Desc   : &yan unfinished object&n
&g3&n) L-Desc   :-
&yAn unfinished object is lying here.&n
&g4&n) A-Desc   :-
&y<not set>&n
&g5&n) Type        : &cUNDEFINED&n
&g6&n) Extra flags : &cNOBITS &n
&g7&n) Wear flags  : &cTAKE &n
&g8&n) Weight      : &c0&n
&g9&n) Cost        : &c0&n
&gA&n) Cost in QP  : &c0&n
&gB&n) Timer       : &c0&n
&gD&n) Values      : &c0 0 0 0&n
&gE&n) Applies menu
&gF&n) Extra descriptions menu
&gQ&n) Quit
Enter choice : 
-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

Each entry is described below:
 
1. &yNamelist&n: This is the list of all keywords, separated by spaces, that
             denotes the object.  For example, you may wish to designate a
             sword with the keywords 'sword weapon steel' to allow a 
             player to pick up that object.
2. &yS-Desc&n: This is the text string shown when a player has this object
           in their inventory, or when using it in some fashion.  Keep as
           brief as possible, but not overly generic.
3. &yL-Desc&n: This is the text string shown to a player when he sees it
           lying in a room.  It should be something like "<Name of obj> is
           lying here."
4. &yA-Desc&n: Do not use.
5. &yType&n: There are a number of types possible for an object, but only
         one is possible at a time.  The list is as follows:

        &gUNDEFINED&n: Do not use.
        &gLIGHT&n: Object is a light source, such as a torch, that will
               illuminate rooms flagged as DARK.
        &gHERB&n: Object is an herb with beneficial or deleterious effects.
        &gHEALING&n: Object provides some type of healing effect.
        &gWEAPON&n: Object is a close combat weapon.  This flag should be
               placed on all objects intended to be wielded.
        &gBOW&n: Object is a missile weapon, requiring the Archery skill
             to be effective.
        &gARROW&n: Object is a missile used as ammunition for BOWs.
        &gTREASURE&n: Object is valuable, such as gold or jewels.
        &gARMOR&n: Object protects the wearer from damage, as a helmet
               or shield.
        &gWORN&n: Object is wearable, such as a shirt or pair of pants.
        &gOTHER&n: Object is not definable as one of the above types.
        &gTRASH&n: Object is worthless.
        &gWAGON&n: Object is a wagon.  See WAGON helpfile.
        &gCONTAINER&n: Object can hold other items, such as a backpack or
                   beltpouch.
        &gNOTE&n: Object can be written on, such as a piece of paper.
        &gLIQ CONTAINER&n: Object can hold liquids, such as a glass or  
                       wineskin.
        &gKEY&n: Object is the key to a lock, such as a locked door.
        &gFOOD&n: Object is edible.
        &gMONEY&n: Object is some form of currency, usually gold.
        &gPEN&n: Object can be used to write on NOTEs.
        &gBOAT&n: Object can be used to traverse water.  Currently not needed.
        &gFOUNTAIN&n: self-explanatory
        &gFURNITURE&n: Object is a piece of furniture.  See the furniture
                   helpfile for further information.
        &gMOUNT FOOD&n: Object is food for mounts, such as horses.  Currently
                    not in use.

Most of these object types can be further specified using entry D, Values. 
For WEAPONs, ARMOR, and similar items, balance rules must be obeyed.
6. &yExtra flags&n: This is a list of additional specifications that can be
                made.  Unlike the Type entry, more than one of these flags
                can be on a single item.

        &gANGREAL&n: Item gives extra mana to the wearer, generally 
                 expressed as a percentage.
        &gSA'ANGREAL&n: Item gives additional mana to the wearer, above
                    that of ANGREALs.  Both of these are subject to balance
                    rules and must have HB approval.
        &gTER'ANGREAL&n: Currently not supported by the code.
        &g!DONATE&n: Item cannot be donated.
        &gDREAM&n: Item exists only in Tel'aran'rhiod.
        &gINVISIBLE&n: Item cannot be seen without holylight or other means
                   of detection.
        &g!TOOL&n: Item cannot be restringed using the 'tool' skill.
        &g!DROP&n: Item cannot be dropped.
        &g!MALE&n: Item cannot be used magically by men.
        &g!FEMALE&n: Item cannot be used magically by women.
        &gSUNG&n: Item has been sung by an Ogier.  Do not set manually.
        &g!PULL&n: Item cannot be pulled.  Generally not set unless the item
               is a WAGON.
        &g!SELL&n: Item cannot be sold in a shop.
        &g!BREAK&n: Item will not wear down due to the wear and tear of
                battle.  Only useful on ARMOR and WEAPONS.
        &g!SAVE&n: Item is not saved in player inventories after they leave
               the game.
        &gUNDEFINED&n: Do not set.

7. &yWear flags&n: This gives a list of locations where the item can be worn.
More than one may be selected, but keep them realistic.  For example, 
no boots being worn on hands.
8. &yWeight&n: How much the item weighs.  Presently this does not do much,
but it should be set anyway for the day when encumbrance is coded to mean 
something.
9. &yCost&n: The coin value of the item.  This should always be greater
than zero.
A. &yCost in QP&n: The item's value in quest points.  This should only be set
if the item is a quest item.
B. &yTimer&n: How many mud hours before the item disappears.  Generally, this
is not set.
D. &yValues&n: Additional information that depends on the object type.  Always
set when appropriate.  Example: you may set the capacity of a CONTAINER here.
E. &yApplies menu&n: This is where you set the bonus/penalties an item gives
when worn/wielded, if any.
F. &yExtra descriptions menu&n: This is where you add any additional 
descriptions you want a player to see when looking at an item.  The extra
descs can all have different keywords.  For example, this is where you may 
wish to describe what the hilt of a sword looks like, or even a gem set into
the pommel.
Q. &yQuit&n: This exits the object editor. After quitting, you will be asked 
if you want your changes to be saved.  If you select no, nothing happens to 
the object.  If you select yes, the changes will only be saved until the next 
crash or reboot.  You must use 'oedit save' to save the item permanently.
#200
PAGE

Usage: page <player | all> <message>

PAGE is used to send a message, along with a beep, to another player.  Use
PAGE ALL to send a message and a beep to everyone in the game.

Examples:

  > page rasmussen Hey, are you still at the keyboard?
  > page all GAME WILL BE SHUTTING DOWN IN 10 MINUTES

Do not abuse this command.
#200
PARDON

Usage: pardon <victim>

Removes killer and thief flags from a player.
#200
POOFIN POOFOUT

Usage: poofin <message>
       poofout <message>

Sets the message seen by players when you use GOTO to move to a different
room.  POOFIN with no argument resets your poofin to the default "appears with
an ear-splitting bang"; POOFOUT with no argument defaults to "disappears in
a puff of smoke."

See also: GOTO
#200
PURGE

Usage: purge [name]

Purge destroys things.  If used with no arguments, it will clear a room of all
mobiles and objects, but will not harm players.  If the argument is an object,
that object (and all of its contents, if any) will be destroyed.  If the
argument is a mobile, the mobile will be destroyed, leaving its inventory and
equipment lying on the ground.

If the argument is the name of a player, the player's inventory and equipment
will drop on the ground and the player will lose his/her connection.  For this
reason, PURGE should only be used on players in disciplinary situations.

Examples:

  > purge
  > purge Pom
  > purge sword
  > purge dragon

See also: DC
#200
RCOPY

Usage: rcopy [-flags>] <source room> <target room>

Makes a copy of <source room> in location <target room> (All rooms
are given as VNUMs. Without any  flags used, everything but extra
descriptions and exits are copied. With the flag -x rcopy will copy all
extra descriptions, given the -e flag. rcopy will copy all exits.  Given
-ex both extra descs and exits will be copied. 

Examples:

  > rcopy 32699 32697
  > rcopy -e 1 25000
  > rcopy -x 25000 9560
  > rcopy -ex 32500 71003

See also: REDIT
#200
REDIT

Usage: redit <vnum>
       redit save <zone>

Edits an existing or creates a new room in the database. This command makes
you enter a menu driven OLC system.

The second alternative makes you save your changes onto disk.

See REDIT2 for an explanation of the menu options.

See also: OEDIT, MEDIT, SEDIT, ZEDIT, RCOPY
#200
REDIT2

When you type redit, you will see the following screen:

-=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=-
-- Room number : [&c32629&n]       Room zone: [&c326&n]
&g1&n) Name           : &yAn unfinished room&n
&g2&n) Description    :
&yYou are in an unfinished room.&n
&g3&n) Room flags     : &cNOBITS&n
&g4&n) Sector type    : &cInside&n
&g5&n) Exit north     : &c-1&n
&g6&n) Exit east      : &c-1&n
&g7&n) Exit south     : &c-1&n
&g8&n) Exit west      : &c-1&n
&g9&n) Exit up        : &c-1&n
&gA&n) Exit down      : &c-1&n
&gB&n) Exit northeast : &c-1&n
&gC&n) Exit southeast : &c-1&n
&gD&n) Exit southwest : &c-1&n
&gE&n) Exit northwest : &c-1&n
&gF&n) Extra descriptions menu
&gH&n) Special       : &cNONE&n
&gQ&n) Quit
Enter choice : 
-=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=-

The various entries are:

1. &gName&n: The 'title' of the room. This is always displayed when a player 
moves into the room, on the top.  Always change this line when making a new 
room.
2. &gDescription&n: The description of the room. This is shown to a player
when he enters the room.  Always change this line when making a new room.
3. &gRoom flags&n: These flags determine certain aspects of the room, and
are explained below.
        &yDARK&n: The room is dark, and requires a light source for normal
              sight. Example: a cellar or dungeon.
        &y!GATE&n: Room cannot be gated to.
        &y!MOB&n: Mobiles cannot enter this room.
        &yINDOORS&n: Weather and time messages are not echoed to the room.
        &yPEACEFUL&n: Fighting and stealing are forbidden in room.
        &ySOUNDPROOF&n: Public channels and the tell channel cannot be
                    used or heard in this room.
        &y!TRACK&n: Players cannot be tracked through this room.
        &y!MAGIC&n: Weaving and grasping cannot be accomplished here.
        &yTUNNEL&n: Only one person at a time is allowed in this room.
        &yPRIVATE&n: Only two people at a time can enter this room.
        &yGODROOM&n: Mortals cannot enter this room.
        &yVERY_DARK&n: Even Wolfkin characters require a light source in
                   this room.
        &yGUILD&n: Only players of the right guild can enter or remain in
               this room.  Only set in guild zones.
        &y!RECALL&n: The recall command is disabled in this room.
        &yOLC&n: Internal use only, do not set.  This flag is code set on
             a room whenever it is being redited, to prevent two
             people from editing the room simultaneously.
        &y*&n: Internal use only, do not set.  This flag is code set on a 
           room whenever someone tracks through it.
        &yWAGON&n: Room is a wagon.  See the helpfile on WAGON for more
               details.
        &yHOUSE&n: Do not set.  Used for the upcoming house code.
        &ySTEDDING&n: Only affects Ogier characters.  Do not use outside
                  of a stedding zone.

4. &gSector type&n: This brings up a list of available sector types, which 
set the movement cost to travel through this room.  Always set appropriately.
5-E. &gExits&n: These entries determine whether there is, or is not, an 
exit in the specified direction, if it has a door, the characteristics of 
that door, and so on.  Please remember not to set exits to nonexistent rooms,
and that you characterize a door identically on either side.  Note that you
can also use RLINK to create exits, but not doors.  You can also write 
exit descriptions with these options.
F. &gExtra descriptions menu&n: This option allows you to describe certain
features about a room that are not present as objects or mobs.  See entry
F in the OEDIT2 helpfile for more information.
G. &gRoom programs&n: These do not work yet. Ignore this option.
H. &gSpecial&n: This allows you to set special features of the room. Do not
set any of these without getting the approval of the Head Builder. 
Q. &gQuit&n: This exits the room editor.  You will be asked if you want your
changes saved.  If you select no, any changes you made are erased.  If you
select yes, the changes are only saved until the next crash or reboot.  You
must use 'redit save <zone number>' to save your changes permanently.
#200
RELOAD

Usage: reload < '*' | all | file >

Reload is used to reload text files such as the MOTD from disk into memory.
reload * reloads all the text files below.

Valid files are:

  background (/mud_dir/lib/text/background)
  credits    (/mud_dir/lib/text/credits)
  handbook   (/mud_dir/lib/text/handbook)
  help       (/mud_dir/lib/text/help)
  immlist    (/mud_dir/lib/text/immlist)
  imotd      (/mud_dir/lib/text/imotd)
  news       (/mud_dir/lib/text/news)
  motd       (/mud_dir/lib/text/motd)
  info       (/mud_dir/lib/text/info)
  policy     (/mud_dir/lib/text/policies)
  wizlist    (/mud_dir/lib/text/wizlist)
  xhelp      (/mud_dir/lib/text/help/*)
  xpolicy    (/mud_dir/lib/text/policies/*)
#200
REROLL

Usage: reroll <player>

REROLL gives a player new stats (i.e., Str, Int, Wis, Dex, Con, and Cha)

See also: STAT
#200
RESTORE

Usage: restore <player | mobile>

RESTORE restores a player or mobile to full hit, mana, and movement points.
If used on immortals, it also sets all skill levels to 100%.
#200
RETURN

Usage: return

RETURN returns you to your regular body if you are switched into a mob.

See also: SWITCH
#200
RLINK

Usage: rlink <dir> <connect|disconnect> <1|2> [target]

Note: [target] is optional.  If excluded, a new room is created.

RLINK creates or removes an exit in the specified direction from the room
it is executed in.  The ending target is the room vnum to link the exit
to.

Using a 1 in the third field specifies a one-way exit, meaning the exit
is created/destroyed only in the room you are presently in.

A 2 specifies a two-way exit, which creates/deletes an opening in both
your present room and the one in the indicated direction.

Rlink is useful in that it is not necessary to redit exits in two rooms
separately; it does all the linking for you.

Example: rlink e connect 2 10001  <-- creates exit east to room 10001
         rlink nw connect 2  <-- creates a new room with next vnum in zone,
                                 and links with an exit northwest
         rlink s disconnect 2  <-- deletes exit to the south on both sides

SEE ALSO: REDIT
#200
ROOMFLAGS

Usage: roomflags

Toggles a flag which causes the virtual room number and room flags, if any,
to be displayed next to room names.
#200
SEDIT

Usage: sedit <vnum>
       sedit save <zone>

Edits an existing or creates a new shop in the database. This command makes
you enter a menu driven OLC system.
Note that you, to create a working shop also have to:
 * create the items you want the shop to sell
 * create the shopkeeper
 * make a room in which the shopkeeper will stand
 * with zedit, load the shopkeeper into the room and load the items
   which he will sell into his inventory.

The second alternative makes you save your changes onto disk.

See SEDIT2 for a decription of menu options.

See also: OEDIT, REDIT, MEDIT, ZEDIT
#200
SEDIT2
 
Before using sedit, you must make sure you have a room for the shop, the
items you want the shop to sell, and a mob to serve as the shopkeeper.
When all that is said and done, you will see the following menu when
you type sedit.

-=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=-
-- Shop Number : [&c10005&n]
&g0&n) Keeper      : [&c10011&n] &yKaren the shopkeeper&n
&g1&n) Open 1      :    &c0&n          &g2&n) Close 1     :   &c28&n
&g3&n) Open 2      :    &c0&n          &g4&n) Close 2     :    &c0&n
&g5&n) Sell rate   : &c1.00&n          &g6&n) Buy rate    : &c0.67&n
&g7&n) Keeper no item : &y%s Alas, I don't sell any of those.&n
&g8&n) Player no item : &y%s Sell me what?&n
&g9&n) Keeper no cash : &y%s I can't afford that!&n
&gA&n) Player no cash : &y%s You are too poor!&n
&gB&n) Keeper no buy  : &y%s I don't trade in such items.&n
&gC&n) Buy sucess     : &y%s That'll be %d coins, thanks.&n
&gD&n) Sell sucess    : &y%s I'll give you %d coins for that.&n
&gE&n) No Trade With  : &cNOBITS&n 
&gF&n) Shop flags     : &cNOBITS&n
&gR&n) Rooms Menu
&gP&n) Products Menu
&gT&n) Accept Types Menu
&gQ&n) Quit
Enter Choice : 
-=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=-

Each entry is described below. 

0. &yKeeper&n: This is the vnum of the mobile that will serve as the 
           shopkeeper.  The name will appear automatically.
1. &yOpen 1&n: This is the first mud-hour that the shop opens.
2. &yClose 1&n: This is the first mud hour the shop closes.  Set to be larger
            than Open 1.
3. &yOpen 2&n: The second mud hour the shop opens, if any.  Set larger than 
           Close 1.
4. &yClose 2&n: The second closing time for the shop.  Set larger than 
            Open 2.
5. &ySell rate&n: This specifies the rate at which a shop sells an object,
              relative to its value.  Always set to 1 or more.  For example,
              a sell rate of 1.5 means the shop will set items at 50% above 
              the listed value for that object (which is set with OEDIT).
6. &yBuy rate&n: This specifies the rate at which the shop buys an object,
             relative to its value.  Always set to 1 or less.  For example,
             a buy rate of .75 means the shop only offers a player 75% of
             the object's value if he sells it to the shop.
7-D. &yMisc. messages&n: These are the strings the player will see for various
                     attempts to buy or sell items, depending on whether they
                     can afford it or not.  %d is the variable for the price.
E. &yNo Trade With&n: Unused.  This is a relic from circle stock code.
F. &yShop flags&n: Unused.
R. &yRooms menu&n: This option allows you to select what room(s) the shop
               exists in.  This must be set, but note that this does not make
               the shop work unless you have the shopkeeper mob in those
               rooms as well.
P. &yProducts menu&n: This allows you to select one items the shop has an
                  unlimited number of.  To make the shop actually sell them,
                  you must give them to the shopkeeper mob in zedit.
T. &yAccept Types Menu&n: This allows you to select what types of objects
                      the shop will buy.
Q. &yQuit&n: This exits the shop editor.  As per the other editors, you must
use 'sedit save <zone num>' to permanently save your changes.

Note that you must have created a room for the shop with redit, and a mobile
shopkeeper using medit.  Use zedit to place the shopkeeper in the room and
to load it with the items you wish it to sell.
#200
SET

Usage: set [ file | player ] <character> <field> <value>

SET is an extremely powerful command, capable of setting dozens of aspects of
characters, both players and mobiles.

SET PLAYER forces set to look for a player and not a mobile; useful for
players with names such as 'guard'.

SET FILE lets you change players who are not logged on.  If you use SET FILE
on a player who IS logged on, your change will be lost.  If you wish to set
a player who is in the game but is linkless, use set twice -- once with the
FILE argument, and once without -- to make sure that the change takes.

For toggled fields (BINARY), the value must be ON, OFF, YES, or NO.

The following are valid fields:

Field          Level Required   Who     Value Type   Decription
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
brief          LVL_GOD          PC      BINARY       Brief mode
invstart       LVL_GOD          PC      BINARY       Invisible @ Start
