#200
STAT

Usage: stat [player | object | mobile | file] <name>

Gives information about players, monsters, and objects in the game.  The type
argument is optional.

STAT PLAYER will search only for players; useful for statting people with
names such as Red or Cityguard.

STAT OBJECT will search only for objects.

STAT MOBILE will search only for monsters.

STAT FILE is used to stat players who are not logged in; the information
displayed comes from the playerfile.

Examples:

  > stat fido
  > stat player red
  > stat mobile red
  > stat file niandra
  > stat object thunderbolt

See also: VSTAT
#200
STRING

Usage: string <type> <name> <field> [<string> | <keyword>]

For changing the text-strings associated with objects and characters.  The
format is:

Type is either 'obj' or 'char'.

Field is one of the following(the names may be abbreviated):

Name                  (the call-name of an obj/char - kill giant)
Short                 (for inventory lists (obj's) and actions (char's))
Long                  (for when obj/character is seen in room)
Title                 (for players)
Description           (For look at.  For obj's, must be followed by a keyword)
Delete-description    (only for obj's. Must be followed by keyword)

Where a string is expected as the last argument, a newline will make you enter
a string mode, and the game will prompt you for new lines to the string until
you exceed the maximum length for the string or you end a line with a '@'.

Mobiles and objects currently cannot be strung.
#200
SWITCH

Usage: switch <monster>

SWITCH is used to take over the body of mobiles; useful for interactive
adventures.  If the monster in which you are switched is killed you will be
returned to your own body.

See also: RETURN
#200
QUESTLOCK
   
Usage: questlock

The QUESTLOCK command will allow/forbid new mortals from joining in a
quest that has already began. Typing the command will toggle this on and
off.
You can always add specific characters with the "set quest <name>" command
without having to make the quest available to everyone again.
#200
SYSLOG

Usage: syslog [off | brief | normal | complete]

The SYSLOG command controls how detailed of an on-line system log you see.
Messages surrounded by '[' and ']' are syslog messages and are in green
if you have color on.

The messages you receive are level dependent.

Examples:

  > syslog complete
  > syslog off

See also: COLOR
#200
"TER'ANGREAL CRAFTING"

First of all: The item TYPE must be OTHER. 
Second      : It must be TAKE'able and HOLD'able. 
Third       : The extra flag TER'ANGREAL must be set (!MALE/!FEMALE might
	      also be used with ter'angreals. 
Fourth      : Edit the values of the Ter'angreal, they are in order of apperance:
		Spellnumber: The number of the spell this Ter'angreal will cast
		 when used. See \c01"HELP SPELL NUMBERS"\c00 for a list of weaves
		 and their number. 
		Casting lvl: At which level will this weave be cast, any 
		 number between 1 and 199 is OK. 
		Mana add: The extra mana this Ter'angreal'll put into the
		 weave for extra boost, anything between 0 and 12000 is ok. 

Exit oedit and save, you have now crafted yer first Ter'angreal. :>

Extra info:
  All flows in the casting will be set to exactly the requirements for the 
  weave, so the flow modifier will be 1. 

  All weaves (where appliable) will be tied. No maintining in other words. 

  Can be used by channies as well as non-channies. (At least until a 
  Channie-only flag is put in. :))

  All casting is done through the ordinary weave-function, arguments is just
  'passed along' from the use-cmd to the cast-cmd. 

See also: "SPELL NUMBERS"
#200
TEDIT

Usage: tedit <file>

This editor allows you to edit the following documents from within the game:
	credits
	handbook
	help
	imotd
	info
	motd
	news

Example: tedit motd  <--  edits the motd shown to morts upon login
